<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON>'s president Wednesday to express solidarity with the rightist government in the face of a fierce guerrilla attack that has left upwards of 500 people dead and more than 1,000 wounded. White House press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> commended President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> for the efforts of the Salvadoran armed forces `` to avoid causing casualties to the civilian population.'' The spokesman said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also pledged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would continue to speak out about <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> and Nicaraguan support for the guerrillas, `` which flies in the face'' of regional peace accords. The four-day-guerrilla offensive appeared stalled as government troops drove the rebels from working-class neighborhoods in fierce combat. The armed forces' air power and numerical superiority combined with lack of popular support for the guerrillas appeared to tilt the battle for the capital in favor of the government. In Friday editions, The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials were accelerating deliveries of munitions and other aid scheduled for delivery to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> he stands behind the Salvadoran government. `` The president said that the -LRB- rebel force -RRB- bears full responsibility for this tragedy and that he wanted to express the solidarity of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people for the great suffering in <LOCATION> Sal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and elsewhere.'' The press spokesman said <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> thanked <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for his support and reported that the armed forces were having increasing success against the guerrillas. Further, <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> told <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> that the government `` would continue to give the highest priority to protecting the civilian population in military operations against those guerrillas that remained,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said.
