<SECOND>PM-Germany-Media,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Media Try to Come to Grips with New-Found Freedoms</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senior editors at <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s state news agency used to dread the daily phone call from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, telling them what to write. Such calls are just a memory now. `` Nobody tells us what to report and what not to report anymore,'' said <PERSON> Ralf </PERSON> <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON>, assistant director general of the <ORGANIZATION> ADN </ORGANIZATION> news agency. `` It's as if someone had removed the brakes on us.'' <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON>, 59, and others said Tuesday that decades of restrictions on reporting have been lifted over the last three weeks in the course of radical changes that toppled the hard-line leadership of <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Honecker </PERSON> and culminated in the opening of the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall. <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON> says he sees ADN evolving from a mouthpiece of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> into a non-partisan news service `` that is there for all readers, for all parties, for all newspapers.'' Acting Chief Editor <PERSON> Hans-Joachim </PERSON> <PERSON> Koppe </PERSON> of the daily <ORGANIZATION> Neue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zeit </ORGANIZATION> also perceives the news media moving toward `` a real pluralism of opinions and parties,'' after shaking off constraints that resulted in some of the world's most slanted and boring reporting. His paper is run by the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> _ one of four parties allowed to survive after the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> assumed sole control in 1949 in exchange for acknowledging Communist supremacy. For decades, that tradeoff was reflected in <LOCATION> Neue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zeit </LOCATION>'s reporting With the exception of sports on the last page, the eight-page edition on Oct. 9 was devoted to celebrations of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s 40th anniversary and the visit of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. A headline from that edition: `` The Idea of Socialism Becomes More Enriched and is Conducive to Joint Action.'' Since then, <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s peaceful revolution has swept <ORGANIZATION> Neue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zeit </ORGANIZATION>'s pages clean of such subservience. `` The Issue is True Pluralism, of Letting the People Decide,'' read one front-page headline. `` Ninety-Three Percent -LRB- of Respondents -RRB- Want a New Election Law,'' read another. An editorial criticized the Communists in a way that would have been unthinkable just three weeks ago, urging `` those who are guilty to be made accountable to the people.'' `` It is just that party leaders and ministers are made accountable to us,'' the editorial continued. `` It is just when property and privileges gained illegally are confiscated. One should be made to take responsibility for political mistakes. And crimes have to be punished.'' State television also is n't what it used to be. Over the past three weeks: _ Chief editor <PERSON> Klaus </PERSON> <PERSON> Schickhelm </PERSON> of the main news program went on the air to apologize to the public for biased and false reporting and pledged `` quick and honest'' news presentation _ `` The <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canal </ORGANIZATION>,'' a rabidly anti-West propaganda program that enraged East Germans for nearly 30 years, was abruptly canceled. _ A <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> session was transmitted live for the first time, giving viewers a chance to see suddenly enlivened legislators call for free elections and criticize the Communist leadership Such changes are appreciated by East Germans, many of whom used to watch West German television to get a feel of what was happening in their country and the world. `` I never used to watch the <PERSON> Aktuelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamera </PERSON>,'' taxi driver <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Schimansky </PERSON> said of the main evening news show. `` But now, I watch it all the time, because I find it keeps me better informed about what is happening here than West German TV does.'' The new-found boldness in reporting also has made reading the newspaper more rewarding. `` I used to be through the newspaper in five minutes,'' said the 46-year-old Schimansky, as he dropped off a passenger near the Checkpoint Charlie crossing point to the West. `` Now, I need about two hours.''
