<HEAD>New Lease on Life for Strife-Torn Civil Rights Panel Clears Committee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, torn by internal feuding and under fire in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, would gain a six-month extension under legislation approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` The time has come in this country to put the petty bickering and the waste of the taxpayers' money on the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> behind us,'' Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sensenbrenner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wis </LOCATION>., told committee members Tuesday The commission will go out of business Nov. 30 unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> extends it. Republicans and Democrats critical of the strife that has wracked the panel have so far been unable to agree on the length of the extension. Approved by the committee, 25-9, was a Democratic-sponsored, six-month extension that would keep on the front burner the question of how to reshape the commission and end its long-running internal feuds. The committee turned down a Republican plan to allow the commission to go out of business for one day only, thus allowing the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to dump any members it opposes. It then would be reconstituted for six years. The Republican plan, offered by <PERSON> Sensenbrenner </PERSON>, was similar to a version recommended to the committee by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration. `` We should not ram through a six-year bill in the closing days of this <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, D-Calif., chief supporter of the Democratic version He said he had initially sought a one-year extension but bowed to a proposal by Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., to cut that time in half Twenty-five years ago, civil rights forces hailed the commission's hearings across the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, its ringing reports on racial injustice and its bold legislative proposals. `` It served as the conscience of the nation,'' says <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Neas </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>. Over the last six years, however, the commission has been snarled in fierce internal fighting. Lately, Democrats and Republicans on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> have joined in slashing its budget. Controversy has dogged commission member <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, its former chairman. He most recently came under fire for a speech to a conservative group. The title was: `` Blacks? Animals? Homosexuals? What is a Minority?'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, who is black, calls himself the only conservative on the commission and says he does `` not believe in coddling people.'' In a 6-1 vote, the commission branded the speech `` thoughtless, disgusting and unnecessarily inflammatory.'' `` Frankly, it is a waste of the taxpayers' money to continue the prattle that has been coming out of the commission for another six months,'' <PERSON> Sensenbrenner </PERSON> said. `` We would be better off with no civil rights commission than with this civil rights commission.'' Hostile exchanges between <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> commission member <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Frances </PERSON> <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> have been at the heart of the controversy, he said. Rep. <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, D-Mass., however, told the committee that `` anyone who was committed to the cause of civil rights who did not spend a lot of time disagreeing with chairman <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> would be derelict in his or her duty, since he is one of the more bizarre public officials in my memory. <PERSON> Sensenbrenner </PERSON> retorted that <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> `` has come up with some bizarre statements of her own.'' He said it was urgently necessary to take action to turn around the course of the commission. `` They have frankly made themselves into a national laughingstock,'' he said.
