<FIRST>r w PM-PensionRights     11-15 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pension Rights,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pension Groups Encourage Workers to Know Their Rights</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Pension Probe, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Addresses at end of article</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Better safe than sorry'' is the motto of a public interest group that says Americans should act as watchdogs for their own pension plans. `` Like millions of Americans, a large part of your savings may be in a pension fund,'' says the Washington-based Pension Rights Center. `` But a Great Dane or a German Shepherd ca n't protect the money in your pension fund.'' The center publishes a booklet, which costs $ 6, titled `` Protecting Your Pension Money.'' It outlines your rights, as well as the rules that your pension plan's administrator must follow. Free pamphlets on the same subject are available from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Persons </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Whether or not you have a pension plan is up to your employer. Only 46 percent of the nation's privately employed, full-time workers are covered by private pension plans. And only 40 million of the 76 million people covered by those plans are insured by the government's <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Pensions for employees working in offices or shops with fewer than 25 employees are not insured by the federal government. Retirement benefits are most commonly based on the number of years worked and final salary. Most plans have age and service requirements before an employee can participate, and similar rules for when the pension can be collected. The Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974, known as ERISA, sets rules for pension plans. All pension plans differ, but overall you have the right to: _ Find out the overall status of your plan by requesting in writing from your employer a `` Summary Plan Description'' outlining your company's plan _ Ask your plan administrator for a copy of your employer's Summary Annual Report, which details your company's _ Obtain a copy of the company's Form 5500, a more detailed financial report, available on written request from the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> Those running your plan must follow a number of rules. Among the most important: _ Your plan managers are required to invest the money with your best interests in mind They may not make investments to benefit themselves or your employer, if these conflict with your interests. _ Administrative costs of running your plan must be reasonable _ To hedge against risks, managers ca n't put all the pension money into one investment, such as a single stock or one piece of real estate If it appears the rules have been broken, you should notify the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. If you suspect the administrators have taken loans from the plan or had conflicts of interest, you should contact the Employee Plans Division of the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION> handles cases of kickbacks and embezzlement. `` The most effective way to convince government investigators to take a look at your problem is to provide them with a short summary of the problems you have found together with the supporting documents,'' the Pension Rights Center says. `` If you can not convince a government agency to investigate your plan, you might want to consider contacting a lawyer,'' it says.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDS: here are addresses for the groups named in this article: Pension Rights Center 918 16th Street NW Suite 704 <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> D.C. 20006 <ORGANIZATION> AARP </ORGANIZATION> Fulfillment 1909 K Street NW <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> D.C. 20049 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 200 </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constitution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ave. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> NW </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> D.C. 20210
