<SECOND>PM-Blood Disorder,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Group Urges Sales Suspension of L-tryptophan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Makers of L-tryptophan are suspending distribution and sales of the dietary supplement because of its possible link to a potentially fatal blood disorder, an industry group says. The Council for Responsible Nutrition called for the temporary sales halt as a `` prudent and cautious course of action'' even though no link has been established between the non-prescription supplement and the disorder. Some companies started halting sales soon after the council called for the action Tuesday afternoon, said <PERSON> J.B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordaro </PERSON>, president of the Washington-based council that represents nutritional supplement companies, including most makers of L-tryptophan. He said he expected virtually all makers of the product to comply with the council's call by Thursday. Officials were investigating 81 unconfirmed cases of the disorder, known as eosinophilia, in 17 states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> on Monday banned L-tryptophan. Oregon's Health Division recommended the product be withdrawn, and health officials in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> recommended that people avoid using L-tryptophan. The council's action pertains to the food supplement that is sold in tablet and capsule form, which is used for sleeplessness and premenstrual syndrome. It does not cover multi-ingredient products that also contain L-tryptophan. `` This action should not be viewed as a product recall but an interim measure pending clarification of the causes of this outbreak,'' the council said. `` Public health agencies investigating have not been able to establish a scientific basis or isolate medical evidence that links L-tryptophan with this disorder,'' the council said. `` In addition, to date <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> and industry testing of L-tryptophan products have not identified any product contamination.'' A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> McLearn </PERSON>, said the agency was satisfied with the industry's action. <PERSON> McLearn </PERSON> said that without a stronger cause-and-effect link, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has no authority to order a recall. He said the strongest action the agency could take was announced Saturday when it advised people taking L-tryptophan to discontinue use of the product. At least 12 different brands of L-tryptophan have been identified as having been used by the individuals who became ill in recent weeks. Eosinophilia is marked by a higher than normal number of white blood cells known as eosinophils. Symptoms include severe muscle pain, fever, joint pain, weakness, swelling of the arms and legs and skin rash.
</TEXT>
