<HEAD>Congress, On Eve of Walesa Speech, Votes Aid to Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is moving rapidly to reinforce <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s dramatic political and economic changes with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars, creating a three-year, $ 657 million aid program and providing the first hard cash to back up that promise. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 99-0 on Tuesday to support new business enterprises, stabilize currency, provide emergency food and encourage democratic institutions in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, on the eve of Solidarity labor leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s speech to a joint meeting of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The measure also included $ 81 million in aid for <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. `` <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, this is for you and a free <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., a primary sponsor of the aid measure Both <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> have been in the forefront of the wave of reform sweeping <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> that includes radical opening of political institutions and restructuring of economies along Western lines. At the same time, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> moved to put the first dollars into the new program, voting 324-93 for a foreign aid bill that includes $ 293 million in the current year, along with another $ 240 million in standby credit and trade insurance. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> measure, a $ 14.6 billion bill providing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to allies around the globe, also offered up to $ 85 million for <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Salvador </ORGANIZATION>'s besieged military and $ 125 million to help Andean countries fight the drug war. But the money bill was the subject of a White House veto threat because of a provision, growing out of the Iran-Contra scandal, which would bar use of foreign aid to entice other countries to carry out policies contrary to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law. The administration believed the language would tie its hands in dealings with allies. Another potentially contentious issue in the $ 14.6 billion bill was defused when the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted 219 to 203 to give President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> the right to withhold $ 15 million for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Population Fund if he finds the agency supports forced abortions or sterilizations in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The measure now goes to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. For <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, major elements of the appropriations measure included a $ 200 million grant to help stabilize <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s battered economy and $ 45 million for a private enterprise development fund Other money would go for environmental cleanup, agriculture and educational and cultural exchanges. The bill creating the long-term aid program represented an apparent truce in a game of one-upsmanship between the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and congressional Democrats over who could provide the biggest reward to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had proposed a $ 455 million program which was immediately labeled `` timid'' by Democrats, who proposed upwards of $ 1 billion in aid. As passed by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the measure offers $ 200 million in currency stabilization, $ 400 million in enterprise funds and $ 125 million in food aid. Recognizing <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s serious economic problems and a reform plan advanced to address them, the bill allocates $ 657 million for that country over three years. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> would receive $ 81 million. Overall, the foreign aid appropriations bill included $ 4.7 billion in military aid and $ 3.2 billion in economic aid for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> friends and allies around the world. Among major earmarks for countries in the bill were $ 3 billion for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and $ 2.1 billion for <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, always the largest aid recipients because of their participation in the Camp David peace process. Other large recipients included <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, with $ 460 million in military and economic aid; <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, $ 500 million in military aid; <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, $ 350 million in military aid; and $ 63 million in military and economic aid for <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>. In addition, the agreement provides $ 160 million for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> contribution to the Multilateral Assistance Initiative for the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, $ 83 million for <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> relief, $ 83 million for <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and $ 30 million in military aid to countries in <LOCATION> Sub-Saharan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.
