<HEAD>Hooded Former Drug Dealer Says Destroy Coca Crops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A convicted drug dealer says the only way to stop the cocaine trade is to destroy the coca crop in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` Cut off the snake's head and the snake will die,'' he said. `` Go after the crop or the chemicals that process the coca. I do n't think anything else will do any good. The witness who wore a black hood to conceal his identity _ `` Mr. Witness,'' the congressmen called him _ insisted to a skeptical <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee Tuesday that stepped up efforts to interdict the drug flow are fruitless. Wiping out the coca crop in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and surrounding <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> nations might result in substitute crops springing up in other regions of the world, he said, adding that such a move would buy time. `` What we need now is a breather. It would take two to three years to re-establish a useable crop of coca,'' he said. `` During that time we could take steps to see that it is not done.'' Such a move, he said, would be `` more practical than what we're doing now. The witness, arrested in 1985 after several years of overseeing huge cocaine shipments from <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, said nothing can stop the flow of cocaine once the coca crop is harvested and processed into the drug. He said the drug importing cartels can change their tactics `` instantly'' to circumvent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> enforcement moves. For example, he said if efforts are concentrated on sealing off borders along the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, the importers say: `` We'll let you have fun there, we'll bring the stuff through <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>.'' The witness was accompanied by a group of federal marshals during his appearance before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on financial institutions supervision, re