<HEAD>Tokyo Market Index Hits Record High; Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The key index on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> ended at a record high Wednesday, while the dollar edged down against the yen. The dollar closed at 143.37 yen, down 0.43 yen from Tuesday's 143.80-yen finish It opened at 143.23 yen and ranged between 143.18 yen and 143.40 yen. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 83.59 points, or 0.23 percent, closing at 35,852.23, yet another high. The index had gained 18.52 points for a record closing of 35,768.64 Tuesday. `` The index rose following Tuesday's release of the domestic wholesale price index,'' said a <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s wholesale price index in October fell by 0.6 percentage points from a month earlier, the first decline in 11 months. The dealer said the decline reassured market players that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s interest rates are no longer likely to rise higher. Lower interest rates encourage stock buying. In currency dealings, the dollar's drop followed a similar downswing overnight in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, triggered by steeper-than-expected slides in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic data. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> reported Tuesday that the nation's retail sales fell 1 percent in October, while industrial production dropped 0.7 percentage points that month. Dealers said market players were inclined to sell the dollar and buy the yen expecting that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> monetary policy will be eased. A Bank of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> trader said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency will contine to move narrowly around its opening level until the release of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures for September, due out in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Thursday.
