<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador-Capital     11-15 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Capital,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>War Permeates San Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An open ambulance speeds down a narrow street, siren screaming. A bleeding woman in a rose-colored dress lies sprawled in the back, surrounded by helmeted rescue workers. What is left of downtown street life pauses for a moment as the war wails past. A woman's hand offering a slice of papaya freezes in midair. Eyes track the truck's swift passage. At the Hospital <PERSON> Rosales </PERSON>, the wounded lie on stretchers lining the hallways. A wounded child stares vacantly into space. Someone mops a pool of blood from the floor. For the first time in a decade of civil war, the capital is the battlefield. Some people try to carry on, despite the fighting, despite the rebel traffic ban and despite the government curfew and state of seige. Most simply stay home. The vast majority of businesses have been shuttered since the offensive began Saturday. Traffic is sparse. Many of those who venture out carry improvised white flags. Dogs bark, rockets whistle, mortars thud and sirens wail. The sounds are sharp, unmuffled by the usual din of traffic. Evening brings a rainbow that arcs from a sunlit volcano into the cloud-darkened sky. A helicopter gunship makes a pass, punctuating the scene with the insistence of war. Combat intensifies with the darkness. Many areas are without power after rebels sabotage power lines. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>'s sleep is disturbed by the sound of a nearby rebel assault. The next morning the fence around his home shows the scars of several bullets. Some areas of the city are full-fledged combat zones. In <LOCATION> Zacamil </LOCATION>, one of the neighborhoods on in northern <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> occupied by leftist guerrillas, a stream of people flowed down the hill Tuesday morning. They said they were afraid of another strafing run by government gunships. They begged reporters to ask the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> to help evacuate them. `` Tell them there are babies here, tell them there are children,'' one woman cried. Other residents stood side by side with rebel fighters. `` The people are making their own decision'' whether to stay or go, insisted rebel leader <PERSON> Claudio </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabindranath </PERSON> <PERSON> Armijo </PERSON>. He led a mix of new recruits, some as young as 13, and battle-hardened fighters from the countryside, the main theater of war before this offensive. The fighters include people, like <PERSON> Armijo </PERSON>, from the top ranks of the rebel <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. The sights and sounds of war have been banned from the airwaves. All broadcasters were put under the aegis of the national network when the offensive began and there is a virtual news blackout. What is broadcast is carefully selected. The head of the armed forces general staff, Col. <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Emilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON>, went on television Monday night to say the rebels controlled no territory. But residents of <LOCATION> Zacamil </LOCATION>, where five-story apartment houses abut settlers' tin shacks, know differently. Food, water and medicine in <LOCATION> Zacamil </LOCATION> were running short by Tuesday, but ammunition was not, the rebels said. Spent shells and broken glass littered the ground. Fire crackled from rebel sharpshooters perched in top floors. An air force helicopter passed high overhead, out of range of rebel groundfire. How long, one fighter was asked, would the rebels try to hold out? `` Until we win or die,'' he said.
</TEXT>
