<HEAD>Upsurge In Sports Cable Broadcasts Defended By Tagliabue, Vincent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Professional football and baseball commissioners say the move of sports programming to cable is making games available to more, not fewer, fans. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Football </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Tagliabue </PERSON> and Baseball Commissioner <PERSON> Fay </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> sat side-by-side during a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Judiciary subcommittee hearing Tuesday, and were grilled by lawmakers about the shift of baseball and football telecasts to <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION> and other cable networks. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> said in a prepared statement that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should get involved because the trend was `` leading to a sports blackout for nearly half of the nation which does not have cable.'' NAB President <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could direct the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to reinstitute anti-siphoning rules, which have not been in place since 1977, to assure viewers access to sports broadcasts. Sen. <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> <PERSON> Specter </PERSON>, R-Pa., asked <PERSON> Tagliabue </PERSON> for a `` flat commitment'' that fans would not begin to be assessed a flat fee to view a broadcast of pro football's jewel, the Super Bowl Such a `` pay-per-view'' arrangement is used for some top-draw boxing matches. `` For the balance of this century, we do not foresee pay-per-view for the Super Bowl game,'' <PERSON> Tagliabue </PERSON> said. He said he could not foresee what might happen after that.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Hawkins Flunks Bush as `Education President'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> says President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the would-be `` education president,'' is blocking the education secretary from doing a good job. Rep. <PERSON> Augustus </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, D-Calif., told reporters Tuesday at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, `` I feel rather presumptive in grading the president but I've been asked to do so. He then harshly criticized <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who pledged to become the `` education president'' if elected. `` There is not a single accomplishment, initiative, or educational credit with which the president can be identified, even if the summit is so regarded,'' said <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, referring to the recent two-day meeting of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and the nation's governors that resulted in a push for national performance goals. However, <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> was kinder to Education Secretary <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON>, noting `` he and I are very, very friendly.'' `` I think he's a fine, honorable man. I think he has good motives,'' said <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>. `` I think that if he was not restrained, he probably would do very well. I think under the restraints, he ca n't.'' <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> said <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> is being hampered by policies pushed by the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which `` I think differ diametrically from his own philosophy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Congressman Would Have Coins Pay to Aid Firefighters</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The sponsor of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill to help firefighters wants to pay for it by having the government mint and sell a commemorative coin. A bill by Rep. <PERSON> Curt </PERSON> <PERSON> Weldon </PERSON>, R-Pa., to create a `` fireservice bill of rights'' would be funded though sale of coins minted to commemorate the bicentennial of the death of <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> The coins had already been planned, and the bill would earmark 25 percent of the money for a <ORGANIZATION> Benjamin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Franklin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION>, with the rest going to help train and equip firefighters, set up a hazardous materials communications network, and help the survivors of firefighters killed in action. <PERSON> Weldon </PERSON> insisted at a hearing of the Science, Space and Technology subcommittee on science, research and technology that the measure was not a tax. He said the firefighters' foundation would take private donations as well. The administration, through <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, said such a sale would provide inadequate revenue.
