<FIRST>r a PM-CosmicExplorer     11-15 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cosmic Explorer,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Launch Now Saturday For Cosmic Explorer on NASA's Last Unmanned Rocket</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After replacing a flawed computer on its last unmanned rocket, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> set Saturday for the launch of the first of several satellites that will reveal an `` unbelievable view of the universe.'' `` Hold on to your hats because this is going to shake up the world of science,'' program scientist <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Caroff </PERSON> said of the Cosmic Background Explorer spacecraft and four observatories that will be placed in <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> orbit during the 1990s. Saturday's launch of the $ 150 million Explorer spacecraft _ the centerpiece of a $ 400 million mission _ `` is going to begin an explosion of knowledge about the universe,'' program manager <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilman </PERSON> told reporters Tuesday at the space agency's Jet Propulsion Laboratory. The 4,850-pound Explorer will provide clues to the development of the universe by measuring radiation left over from the `` big bang,'' the explosion scientists say created the universe 15 billion years ago. <PERSON> Gilman </PERSON> said the Explorer will be followed by the launches of what <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> calls its `` great observatories'' _ the <ORGANIZATION> Hubble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telescope </ORGANIZATION> next March, the <ORGANIZATION> Gamma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observatory </ORGANIZATION> in June, the Advanced X-ray Astrophysics Facility in 1997 and the Space Infrared Telescope Facility in 1999. `` These are going to provide us with an unprecedented, unbelievable view of the universe,'' <PERSON> Caroff </PERSON> said in an interview. `` We will see things we have n't even imagined.'' The Explorer is scheduled for launch from <ORGANIZATION> Vandenberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> during a 30-minute period starting at 6:24 a.m. PST Saturday, said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattson </PERSON>, project manager at <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Goddard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Greenbelt </LOCATION>, Md. The launch had been scheduled for Friday, then was delayed until Sunday because of a malfunctioning rocket guidance computer. But the computer was replaced so quickly last weekend that the launch was moved again, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Eaton </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> rocket official. The solar-powered satellite will be carried into a near-polar orbit by a 116-foot-tall <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> rocket _ the last unmanned, expendable rocket ever to be launched by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> will continue to launch manned shuttles and possibly unmanned cargo shuttles with reusable boosters. But <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> or private companies will charge <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> to launch any payloads that require unmanned expendable rockets. After a 30-day shakedown in orbit, the Explorer will spend up to two years measuring `` cosmic background radiation,'' which makes up about 2 percent of the static on a television set. It includes microwaves, heat and other electromagnetic radiation given off by the big bang. The Explorer will measure `` the collective glow of all the stars and galaxies and whatever else has been there since the beginning,'' project scientist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mather </PERSON> said. He said <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> will share information from the mission with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which has flown one similar research mission and plans two others.
</TEXT>
