<HEAD>Stocks in Tokyo Hit Record High; Dollar Closes Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s key index rose to a record high today, while the dollar closed lower against the Japanese yen. The dollar ended trading at 143.37 yen, down 0.43 yen from Tuesday's close of 143.80 yen. The currency opened lower at 143.23 yen and ranged between 143.18 yen and 143.40 yen. `` Trading today was totally directionless and boring,'' said a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Mitsui </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on condition of anonymity. `` Ahead of the release of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures, the dollar-yen rate moved only narrowly.'' The trader said <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> is expecting the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit for September to shrink to $ 8.5 billion. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s trade figure announcement is scheduled for Thursday. On the stock exchange, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues gained 83.59 points, or 0.23 percent. It ended at 35,852.23, renewing the record high for the third-consecutive time since Monday. The index, which has been rising since last Wednesday, has gained more than 580 points. The index slowed its upward movement in the afternoon session as participants sold for profit-taking and arbitrary deals, which resulted in wild fluctuations in the index, dealers said. <PERSON> Kazuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nomura </PERSON>, a dealer with <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, said market players' buying incentive was not strong enough for a larger one-day gain even after a report that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s wholesale price index fell by 0.6 percentage points from a month earlier. It was the first drop in the last 11 months. `` Investors would n't start buying all of a sudden just because of the wholesale price index, becuase our domestic short term interst rate has n't fallen,'' he said. `` Market players will increase buying gradually as they make sure external economic factors are stable enough,'' <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> added. An estimated 1.2 billion shares changed hands on the first section, up from Tuesday's 900 million. Among the winners were construction, railway and financial issues.
