<HEAD>Dean of Yo-Yo Men Dead at 80</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> `` Barnie'' <PERSON> Akers </PERSON>, one of the original <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> yo-yo men who died at age 80, was remembered as a man with a smile on his face and a yo-yo in each hand. <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> died Friday at a <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION> hospital. A memorial service has not been scheduled. <PERSON> Akers </PERSON>' uncle, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON>, popularized the toy in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> during the Great Depression and set up an exhibition schedule with dozens of men traveling from town-to-town, telling stories and selling yo-yos. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Crump </PERSON>, editor of Yo-Yo Times, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, D.C.-based magazine for yo-yo enthusiasts, said Tuesday that <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> was one of the best. `` He was probably the most important link with the great yo-yo years,'' <PERSON> Crump </PERSON> said. `` He actually almost single-handedly created the yo-yo contest,'' a competition designed to increase yo-yo sales. `` I will remember him with a smile on his face and two yo-yos in his hands,'' said <PERSON> Crump </PERSON>, who last saw <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> last winter while in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> to record music to yo-yo by. <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> never married. He said in an interview last summer that a yo-yo man's life, like the toy, is up and down. `` I had a few girlfriends, but they did n't realize that if you do something like this 10 months a year, it gets tiring. I would travel 800 miles in a day just to get to a new market,'' <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> said. `` If you get married, a woman thinks she would like that, like it was a two-week vacation. Not many would like it. Not for 50 years.'' <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> had surgery for prostate problems during the summer and fought lymphoma. He died in the hospital, but his brother, <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>, another yo-yo man who left the trade, said he believed <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> died of a weak heart. <PERSON> Barnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> did n't like calling the yo-yo a toy, saying it taught too many skills _ like eye-and-hand coordination and discipline. In his spiels, he used to give a history of the yo-yo, telling how ancient vases discovered in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> show wooden knobs suspended on strings. `` Go back before the birth of Christ and you can see how the string is tied on their fingers,'' <PERSON> Akers </PERSON> said.
