<TEXT>
 A fire that injured 31 people on the amphibious assault ship USS Inchon apparently was caused by a short circuit in an electrical compartment, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said. Twelve people were hospitalized; the others treated and released. The fire, which started about 9:30 a.m. Tuesday and was extinguished in about 40 minutes, was one of a series of recent accidents that prompted the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> later in the day to order a 48-hour halt to all normal operations for a review of safety procedures. In the past three weeks, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has experienced 10 serious accidents in which 10 people have been killed or lost at sea and at least 53 have been injured. The recent series of accidents followed the April 19 explosion on the battleship USS <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> in which 47 sailors died. The <LOCATION> Inchon </LOCATION> fire broke out as the ship was in the <ORGANIZATION> Metroc </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> shipyard for routine repair work. Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION>, said the blaze apparently was caused by a short circuit and that most of the damage was to electrical cables and insulation in the shore power compartment. There also was smoke and heat damage to the hangar deck. The compartment holds cables from the pier bringing electricity to the ship. Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON>, another <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said 23 sailors and eight civilians were taken to area hospitals. The condition of the 12 admitted for smoke inhalation ranged from stable to serious, according to the hospitals. The 602-foot troop and helicopter carrier has a crew of 675 and can hold up to 2,000 Marines and 20 helicopters when on deploy