<HEAD>Soybean Farmers' Lawsuit Accuses BOT of Illegal Price Manipulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> is denying farmers' allegations that it illegally manipulated soybean prices with an emergency order last summer The order led to a 20 percent drop in soybean prices along with corresponding declines in other commodities, and caused heavy financial losses among family farmers nationwide, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> says. The group, a lobbying organization that represents small farmers and rural business people in 34 states, and family farmers from leading soybean-producing states, filed a federal lawsuit Tuesday against the <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION>. The lawsuit seeks more than $ 100 million in damages. The complaint stems from the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s emergency action July 11 ordering traders to reduce their holdings in soybean futures contracts. The board's move was widely viewed as an effort to break up an attempt to corner the market by <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finanziaria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION>, an Italian company and one of the world's largest soybean processors. `` The <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION>'s order was a bad faith and self-serving action initiated by the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION>'s dominant grain merchants and futures traders to create profits for their accounts and for their clients,'' said <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanner </PERSON>, AAM's president and an <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> soybean farmer. <PERSON> Sanner </PERSON> spoke at a news conference at a downtown hotel, accompanied by about 25 other farmers from <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOC