<HEAD>Crackdown Continues against Sinhalese Extremists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Troops raided a clandestine radio station and captured its operator in a dragnet that is decimating the leadership of an extremist group of Sinhalese nationalists, military officials said today. In addition, the bodies of 31 suspected Sinhalese extremists were discovered at daybreak in the central hills, the officials said. They blamed the killings on pro-government vigilante groups. The government's 2-year-old battle to subdue the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> took a dramatic turn Monday with the reported capture and killing of the group's senior leader, <PERSON> Rohana </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijeweera </PERSON> According to a military source, the avowed Marxist `` sang like a bird'' about the whereabouts of his top lieutenants. In less than 18 hours, <PERSON> Wijeweera </PERSON> and the front's No. 2 and No. 3 men were killed by security forces, according to government announcements. More than 6,000 people have been killed since August 1987 in violence associated with the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>'s assassination campaign targeting governing officials and supporters The front professed outrage that the Sinhalese-dominated government made concessions to the Tamil minority, and its battle escalated into a challenge of the government's right to exist. The military officials said the raid on the front's clandestine radio station was carried out Tuesday night in <LOCATION> Boralesgamuwa </LOCATION>, six miles southeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. The front member in charge of the station, <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Costa </PERSON>, was captured and radio equipment worth $ 1.3 million seized, according to the officials, who can not be identified under briefing rules. The short-wave radio station was called Voice of the Revolution. It broadcast three days a week, varying its hours to avoid jamming, and transmitted <PERSON> Wijeweera </PERSON>'s speeches, revolutionary songs and allegations of government atrocities. The front, as well as human rights activists and opposition politicians, have long accused the government of fielding or tolerating death squads bent on wiping out the front. Some government officials have privately acknowledged that `` excesses'' may have occurred, but they usually blamed the killings of suspected front members on shadowy vigilante groups. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ranjan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijeratne </PERSON> claimed Tuesday that six of the front's seven Politburo members had been killed. But the military officials said today the Politburo had expanded to nine members, of whom seven were known to have been killed. Although killings blamed on the front have tapered off this week, it is too soon to say whether the front is finished or simply regrouping. The bodies of the suspected front members were found in two locations in the center of the island Wednesday. Twenty-three badly mutilated bodies were discovered in <LOCATION> Keppitipola </LOCATION>, about 65 miles east of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. Eight more bodies were found in <LOCATION> Kandy </LOCATION>, 55 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. The violence by the Sinhalese extremists erupted after the Sri Lankan government signed an Indian-sponsored peace accord on July 29, 1987, in an effort to end a Tamil insurrection that started in 1983. The accord spawned a Sinhalese backlash as members of the ethnic majority accused their government of making too many concessions to the Tamil minority. Tamils, who make up 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people, are mostly Hindus and claim the predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinhalese </ORGANIZATION> majority discriminated against them in jobs and education. Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the population, have dominated the government and military since <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, formerly called <ORGANIZATION> Ceylon </ORGANIZATION>, became independent from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in 1948.
