<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> today made a final stride toward full civilian rule as voters cast ballots in the country's first popular presidential election in nearly three decades The vote, on the 100th anniversary of the founding of the Brazilian Republic, follows two decades of rapid economic development in spite of massive foreign debt and widespread poverty. The favorite is a conservative former state governor, <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reconstruction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, but he is not expected to win enough votes to avoid a runoff with one of two top two leftist candidates. Early reports indicated voting was peaceful across the country. In <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>, voters waited good-humoredly in huge lines that snaked around city blocks, despite a threat of rain. Many voted early to take advantage of the national holiday, which marks the 100th anniversary of the founding of a republic that overthrew Emperor <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> II. Brazilians lined up to vote hours before the polls opened at 8 a.m. -LRB- 5 a.m. EST -RRB-. Polls were to close at 5 p.m., with partial results expected at around 9 p.m.. An official projection of the winner was due Saturday <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON>'s attacks on President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> for 1,300 percent annual inflation and widespread corruption have struck a chord with many of the 82 million registered voters, most of whom earn less than $ 36 a week. In a national TV address Tuesday night, <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> called the election `` an extraordinary spectacle'' that demonstrated `` the flourishing of Brazilian democracy.'' `` The democratic transition is complete,'' said <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>, who was chosen in 1985 by an electoral college after the military ended 21 years of rule. `` God has won in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>.'' Fighting for second place are two leftists _ ex-governor <PERSON> Leonel </PERSON> <PERSON> Brizola </PERSON>, who pledges West European-style socialism, and Rep. <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Inacia </PERSON> <PERSON> Lula </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, a former factory worker and strike leader who wants a `` workers' republic,'' with nationalized banks and cancellation of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s $ 110 billion foreign debt. If no candidate wins a majority _ and it's doubtful anyone will _ the top two vote-getters will meet in a runoff Dec. 17. <PERSON> Collor </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mello </PERSON> had a comfortable lead, but far short of a majority in the 21-candidate field, according to two opinion polls announced Tuesday. Many voters wore red bandanas, the symbol of <PERSON> Brizola </PERSON>, who was about even with <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> in voter surveys. But in <LOCATION> Brasilia </LOCATION>, the capital, election officials made <PERSON> Brizola </PERSON> sympathizers take off the bandanas to vote. Other than <PERSON> Brizola </PERSON> or <PERSON> Lula </PERSON>, only two other candidates were given any chance of squeaking into the No. 2 spot: center-leftist Sen. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Covas </PERSON>, and rightist Rep. <PERSON> Paulo </PERSON> <PERSON> Maluf </PERSON>. The two-month campaign has been marred by some personal insults, but enthusiastic crowds have gathered at street rallies across this nation of 150 million people, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s largest. <PERSON> Silvio </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>, a television personality, tried to enter the race at the last minute, but officials ruled he had violated election rules. Paper ballots with squares beside each candidate's name were waiting at 250,000 polling stations, from the southern plains to the remote jungle villages in the northwestern <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> region. Special stations were set up for the blind and for the estimated half-million people with leprosy. In some places, voting equipment had to be carried in by canoe or on mules. Federal troops were stationed in 39 of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s 4,445 counties _ mostly in the remote north and northwest _ to keep order and to prevent last-minute campaigning. Brazilians under 47 _ nearly 73 percent of the electorate _ have never voted for president. In the last election in 1960, <PERSON> Janio </PERSON> <PERSON> Quadros </PERSON> won, but he stunned the nation by saying he was plagued by `` occult forces'' and resigned after seven months in office. His vice president, <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Goulart </PERSON>, took over but was ousted in a military coup in 1964. The military regime banned direct voting for president but it was restored by a new constitution enacted last year. Voting is mandatory for everyone between age 18 and 69. And for the first time in the country's history, 16 - and 17-year-olds may vote, though it's not mandatory Some 3.3 million _ more than half of those eligible _ have registered. The election comes a century after republicans in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> overthrew <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s only independent monarchy.
