<HEAD>Business Inventories Rise, Sales Drop in September</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Business inventories rose 0.2 percent in September, while business sales dropped 0.3 percent, the government reported today. The combination of the accumulation of goods on shelves and backlots rising faster than sales could be bad news for the economy. If inventories were to pile up excessively, it could mean cutbacks in production and a loss of jobs. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said inventories climbed to a seasonally adjusted $ 791.8 billion in September, following a gain of 0.4 percent in August. Business sales, meanwhile, dropped to a seasonally adjusted $ 524.6 billion after advancing 3 percent in August. The September business activity produced an increase in the ratio of sales to 1.51, meaning it would take 1.51 months to exhaust inventories at the September pace. The ratio was 1.50 in August. Retailer backlogs were up 1 percent in September and could be worse in October. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported on Tuesday that retail sales last month dropped a full 1 percent that included a 5.1 percent decline in car sales. On the other hand, manufacturers inventories, which represent about 45 percent of the total, slipped 0.1 percent and wholesale backlogs dropped 0.3 percent. Manufacturers' sales, on the other hand, fell 1.6 percent in September. Retailers' and wholesalers' sales both were up 0.7 percent. Overall inventories were 6.4 percent above those of a year ago. Sales increased 6.7 percent over September 1988.
