<HEAD>Ethnically Mixed Jury Seated in Case That Sparked Riot</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead and 2nd graf; SUBS 6th graf pvs, `The defense ...'
with 2 grafs to UPDATE with defense's opening arguments. SUBS 13th graf
pvs, `Decisions by ...' to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The trial of a Hispanic policeman in the slaying of a black motorcyclist opened today with the prosecution arguing that the officer was in no danger and did not have to fire the shot that set off three days of riots. Circuit Judge <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Farina </PERSON> cleared the way Tuesday for the manslaughter trial of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> officer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> by refusing to move the case out of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. He rejected defense arguments that the threat of violence hung over the trial and could frighten jurors into convicting <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> to avoid another riot. Assistant State Attorney <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Horn </PERSON> told the racially mixed jury, seated after three weeks of questioning, that the 31-year-old officer failed to act as a prudent policeman should have in the slaying of <ORGANIZATION> Clement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION>, 23. `` It was not a life-or-death situation. It was not a split-second decision, and he did not have to shoot,'' said <PERSON> Horn </PERSON>. He said <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> shot <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> in the head after taking two steps into the street and putting himself closer to the path of <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> speeding motorcycle, which was being chased by a patrol car Defense attorney <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, in his opening arguments, said the shooting `` had nothing to do with race.'' `` Officer <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> did not shoot his gun because he's a Hispanic. <PERSON> Clement </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> was not shot because he is black,'' <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said. But within moments, he said, `` race had everything to do with this case'' as a crowd formed in a prelude to a night of rioting. The Jan. 16 shooting, which also led to the death of <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> passenger, exploded into three days of rioting One looter was shot to death, 11 people were wounded by gunfire and 13 buildings were burned down. Some black leaders said the jury's ethnic mixture _ two blacks, one Hispanic and three non-Hispanic whites _ could head off a repeat of rioting that followed acquittals by all-white juries in 1980 and 1984 of two other officers who had killed blacks. `` The fact that the jury resembles the tri-ethnic balance of this community goes a long way to reducing that level of tension,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s Community Relations Board. A televised forum Tuesday night in the predominantly black <LOCATION> Overtown </LOCATION> neighborhood where the shooting occurred illustrated the community's continuing anger, as many participants complained that they were mistreated by Hispanics who arrived in this country only recently. The anger led the defense to enter into the record scores of items showing that more violence was expected if <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> was acquitted. The exhibits included violence-threatening posters by the `` Overtown Comrades,'' and documents showing police contingency plans to combat a riot if <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> is found innocent. Decisions by the judge have sharply limited how much the defense can reveal to jurors about the slain motorcyclist's police record and allegations that he was picking up drug profits the night of the killing. `` We have to start out with the the court already excluding 75 percent of our defense,'' <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` Needless to say, we're operating under a great handicap.'' The shooting took place during the week of the Super Bowl in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. The Colombian-born <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> and his partner were on an <LOCATION> Overtown </LOCATION> street, talking to the victim of a minor crime. As they talked, another squad car was chasing down a speeding motorcycle driven by <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> and carrying his friend <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON>, 24. When the motorcycle turned onto the street where <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> was standing, the officer fired one shot, killing <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> instantly and sending the motorcycle crashing into a car. <PERSON> Blanchard </PERSON> died later. <PERSON> Lozano </PERSON> was charged with two counts of manslaughter. If convicted on both counts, he would face a maximum penalty of 60 years imprisonment. Within an hour after the shooting, a mob gathered at the scene and began pelting officers with rocks and bottles, starting the rioting. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> was found to have high levels of alcohol and THC _ the active chemical in marijuana _ in his blood at the time of his death. He also had 5.5 grams of marijuana and $ 1,500 in his pocket, facts the defense contends showed he was a drug dealer desperate enough to run down a policeman to avoid arrest. The city later set up a commission to examine the roots of the racial disturbance, the fourth to hit <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> in the 1980s. The first occurred in 1980 after an all-white jury in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> acquitted a group of <ORGANIZATION> Metro-Dade </ORGANIZATION> policemen in the fatal beating of black insurance executive <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> McDuffie </PERSON>. The case was moved to <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> because of pretrial publicity. In 1982, a riot broke out when <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> policeman <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON> entered an <LOCATION> Overtown </LOCATION> video arcade and shot and killed <PERSON> Nevell </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a black. Two years later, violence broke out again when an all-white jury acquitted <PERSON> Alvarez </PERSON> of manslaughter.
