<HEAD>Draft Laws on Civil Rights Under Review in Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government panel has proposed revising laws on assembly and association to comply with international human rights accords without discarding traditional Communist principles, an official said today. The state-run <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> submitted the three draft laws to Premier <PERSON> Ladislav </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamec </PERSON>, who on Tuesday announced that Czechoslovaks wishing to travel to the West will no longer need exit visas, beginning Jan. 1. Despite some easing of restrictions, however, the hard-line government continued to crack down on dissent. A court in <LOCATION> Bratislava </LOCATION> on Tuesday sentenced an activist who urged his countrymen to honor those killed in the 1968 <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact invasion that crushed reforms in <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Zbynek </PERSON> <PERSON> Vokrouhlicky </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that worked out the draft laws, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> they will go to a legislative commission before being considered by <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, probably in the spring. The Communist Party organ Rude Pravo on Tuesday said the committee submitted the drafts to <PERSON> Adamec </PERSON> on Nov. 1O. Copies of the drafts could not be obtained immediately, and there were few details on their contents. <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION> is rewriting its laws to conform with human rights commitments signed at a 35-nation conference in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> early this year. Those accords commit the signatory nations to allow freer travel and guarantee human rights. It was not immediately clear if the laws under discussion will translate into more freedoms for the country's population. <PERSON> Adamec </PERSON> said the easing of travel, which has been introduced gradually over the past two years, was designed to reduce bureaucracy and contribute to the `` satisfaction of its citizens.'' Czechoslovaks have been allowed to travel more freely than their counterparts in other hard-line Communist countries, and Western analysts said the new rules will not have a marked effect on who will be allowed to travel. People wishing to travel west still must apply for visas from the country of destination and must prove they have sufficent hard currency to cover travel expenses. Analysts, speaking on condition of anonymity, said there was no indication that political activists, many of whom have had their passports confiscated, would be allowed to travel under the new regulations. In <LOCATION> Bratislava </LOCATION>, a court sentenced activist <PERSON> Miroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Kusy </PERSON> to an eight-month suspended sentence after a two-day trial and acquitted three others who signed a statement urged Slovaks to mark the 21st anniversary of the 1968 invasion. The court refused the defendants' request to be tried together with a fifth activist, <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carnogursky </PERSON>, whose case goes to trial separately next week. He could face up to 10 years in jail.
