<HEAD>German Drama Forces Britain to Rethink its Place in Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The drama in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> is forcing <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to ponder anew its place in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Some analysts say now is the time to get into closer step with the Continent, to join forces in order to absorb a unified German colossus and thus render it harmless. Others argue the opposite: that as the old order unravels and long-held certainties disintegrate, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> should keep its distance and wait for the dust of the crumbling <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall to settle. The question of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s place in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> is an old one, but it had become urgent well before the momentous changes overtook <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and the Germanys. The 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, of which <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is a member, is to become a single tariff - and passport-free trading bloc at the end of 1992, and has ambitious plans for monetary union and Europe-wide standards on workers' rights and social welfare Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, the crusading free-marketeer, believes these are corporatist tendencies, and that the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> bureaucracy in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> is trying to foist on her the very socialist constraints she has fought for 10 years to eradicate in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Economic and monetary union, which <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> is pressing, would be an intolerable encroachment on national sovereignty, says Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, she insists, is primarily a trading bloc, and that by unshackling the markets, abolishing currency controls and opening <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to outside investment, she is being a good European. She repeated this position Monday, signaling that events in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> had not changed her mind at all. But the conflicting reactions to her speech underlined the differing attitudes. While <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> praised `` Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s realism,'' the Guardian denounced her as `` the supreme nitpicker of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' Britons who share Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s view `` tend to see the internal market as the end of a process, while the others see it as the beginning of something more dynamic,'' said <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Bogdanor </PERSON>, a constitutional expert at <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Until recently, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s approach seemed like smart politics. The British never have shared the Continent's romantic, philosophical notion of `` <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' They sometimes seem to relish being odd nation out, whether in refusing to join the exchange rate mechanism that harmonizes the <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> currencies, or in resisting attempts by <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> to impose new health warnings on cigarette packs. They cling to what sets them apart, whether it's driving on the left or measuring distances in miles. Their biggest-circulation newspaper repeatedly derides the French as `` Frogs,'' and union featherbedding is known as `` Spanish practices.'' In the election campaign for the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> in June, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> built its propaganda around the specter of interfering <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> bureaucrats, complete with feeble puns about force-feeding the British on <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> sprouts. But the <ORGANIZATION> Tories </ORGANIZATION> were routed by the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, and many analysts sensed a sea change in public opinion. Perhaps, it was suggested, Europe-bashing was no longer a vote-catcher. The issue of the exchange rate mechanism triggered a crisis last month that prompted the resignation of <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, chancellor of the exchequer and architect of the boom of the mid-1980s. Now comes a new and bigger challenge in the shape of <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. The pro-integrationists paint a scenario of a united <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> with an economy as big and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s combined. To prevent <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> going neutral and drifting to the new markets of <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> must tighten its bonds, thus tying <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> inextricably to the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> and dampening any temptation by German to flex its nationalist muscle. The counterargument says harmonization of social law and monetary union are difficult enough when economies as different as <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s are involved. <LOCATION> Add </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and later, perhaps, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, and harmonization begins to look like a joke. `` -LRB- For -RRB- those who worry about a <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> getting back to its old style through reunification, the only answer is to bind <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> more tightly and tightly to the Community,'' says former Prime Minister <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Heath </PERSON>, who took <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> into the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> in 1973. `` If <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> is going to be bound more tightly into the Community, then we in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> have got to be as well,'' he said Wednesday. `` If we drag our feet, then they'll go ahead and just leave us outside.''
