<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The staff of the <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, consisting mainly of career <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members, gave a collective gasp when Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> cheerfully said he hoped to see them all in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> soon. But <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, giving a pep talk to the embassy staff, assured them he was just being friendly, that he thought they were doing a great job improving relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and that the Solidarity-led government has no plans to call them home. `` I am not taking the place of the government. I am not replacing anybody at the embassy,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said. That was good news for Ambassador <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinast </PERSON>, who served as deputy foreign minister in the communist-led government that preceded Solidarity to pwer and who has been working long hours since then to rally <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic support for the new reform government. The embassy staff played virtually no role in arranging the <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> visit, which was sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> labor federation. But its diplomats have had their hands full getting ready for visits by many Polish government dignitaries and an unending stream of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressional and administration figures headed for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ryszard </PERSON> <PERSON> Krystosik </PERSON>, the No. 2 embassy official, said in an interview this week. Many of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s foreign service professionals shared the conciliatory sentiments expressed by <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>. `` We should forget our differences,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> told them. `` We have had many over the last 45 years. Many of those were caused by others.'' `` This is the time for ... all Poles to work together for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> told the diplomats, assembled in the second floor reception room of the stately turn-of-the century mansion atop <LOCATION> Meridian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. He spoke to them Tuesday during a hectic week, and his remarks were recounted by three Poles who were present. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, who is chairman of the Solidarity trade union but holds no government post, arrived in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Monday on a trip that includes numerous honors as well as non-stop exhortations for Americans to send aid and investment to bolster the Polish reforms. His remark about seeing the Polish diplomats soon in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, delivered at the end of a short pep talk, was taken in the same good humor it was made, said one Pole who was present. `` It did n't have any overtones at all,'' said a Polish diplomat who spoke on condition he not be further identified. `` He was very courteous and was very well received.'' Although courtesy can not entirely ease the tension caused in the diplomatic corps by the fall of the communist government after 45 years in power, <PERSON> Krystosik </PERSON> said the embassy staff is dedicated to seeking <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to bolster the <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s reform government. `` We know very well how important is the role of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as the leader of the Western world. We know very well the initiative of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> organizing and sponsoring assistance to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, a program that paves the way for the implementation of Polish reforms,'' he said. `` The embassy presents the policy line of the government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON>,'' the Solidarity adviser that heads the government, said <PERSON> Krystosik </PERSON>. Besides, said other Polish diplomats, the presence of a Solidarity rather than a communist government in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> has eased one of their main tasks, promoting U.S.-Polish friendship. Polish diplomats, showing a reporter around the embassy this week, eagerly pointed out icons of Polish-American friendship, including a letter to <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> from <PERSON> Thaddeus </PERSON> <PERSON> Kosciusko </PERSON>, a Pole who served as a colonel in the American Revolution then returned to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and led two uprisings against Russian domination. In one corner of the main reception area stands a Steinway grand piano owned by <PERSON> Ignace </PERSON> <PERSON> Paderewski </PERSON>, who was Polish premier in 1919 and who performed many times in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as a reknowned concert pianist. One Polish diplomat played a few bars on the piano, looked up thoughtfully and said, `` we really ought to get this thing tuned.''
