<HEAD>TV Broadcasts Radical's Appeal For Peace Hours After He Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government TV on Wednesday broadcast an appeal for peace by a radical Sinhalese leader that was videotaped while he was in custody and hours before he was shot to death by government troops. Officials also reported finding the bodies of 31 suspected Sinhalese radicals Wednesday and blamed the killings on vigilantes in favor of the Sinhalese-dominated government in a country wracked by ethnic and factional strife. `` I appeal to all my followers to give up their armed struggle against the government and take to the democratic process to achieve our goals,'' said <PERSON> Rohana </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijeweera </PERSON>, the founder of the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, in the broadcast. <PERSON> Wijeweera </PERSON>, who was captured Sunday, voluntarily made the appeal for peace and `` sang like a bird'' about the whereabouts of his top lieutenants, said a senior military source. He and the front's No. 2 and No. 3 men were shot and killed within the next 18 hours, according to government announcements. The avowed Marxist, who used to have a beard and mustache, was clean-shaven and the television clip showed him wearing a red beret and a white shirt. He looked nervous but appeared to be in good health while making the Sinhalese-language broadcast. The government said <PERSON> Wijeweera </PERSON> led security personnel to the group's <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> headquarters Monday to question D.B. <PERSON> Herath </PERSON>, the third-ranking leader of the front. `` Herath pulled a pistol and began firing at <LOCATION> Wijeweera </LOCATION> and troops opened fire, killing both of them,'' said Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ranjan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijeratne </PERSON>. The front's No. 2 man, <PERSON> Upatissa </PERSON> <PERSON> Gamanayake </PERSON>, was killed while trying to escape capture Monday, the government said. Political leaders sypathetic to the front predicted more violence could follow the death of <LOCATION> Wijeweera </LOCATION>, whose personal safety had been guaranteed by President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Dias </PERSON> <PERSON> Bandaranaike </PERSON>, leader of the <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, said the public would not believe the government's version of <PERSON> Wijeweera </PERSON>'s death. The 31 bodies of suspected members of the group were discovered Wednesday in the central hills and were likely killed by pro-government vigilante groups, said the officials, who can not be identified under briefing rules. More than 6,000 people have been killed since August 1987 when the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> started assassinating government officials and supporters. The front professed outrage that the Sinhalese-dominated government was making concessions to the Tamil minority, and its battle escalated into a challenge of the government's right to exist. Tamils, who make up 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people, are mostly Hindus and claim the predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinhalese </ORGANIZATION> majority discriminate against them in jobs and education.
