<FIRST>r w AM-BusinessInventories     11-15 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Inventories,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts See Warning in Inventory Growth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Growth of business inventories outpaced business sales in September, the government said Wednesday in a report that analysts said contained a warning of growing backlogs due to the slowing economy. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that inventories held on shelves and backlots climbed 0.2 percent to a seasonally adjusted $ 791.8 billion after advancing 0.4 percent in August. Business sales, on the other hand, fell 0.3 percent to a seasonally adjusted $ 524.6 billion following a 3 percent gain the previous month. The business activity produced a slight increase in the inventory-to-sales ratio to 1.51, meaning it would take 1.51 months to exhaust inventories at the September pace. It was 1.50 in August. `` At the moment, the ratios do not appear excessive,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` But they show the first signs of increases related to a declining business climate.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON>, chief economist at the <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> agreed that on the surface the report suggests inventories are not yet a problem. `` But there are some warning signals in it of some excess at the consumer level,'' he said. Inventories often rise during periods of slow economic growth as output exceeds demand, a process that could lead to production cuts and loss of jobs. The economy has been experiencing sluggishness as the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> tries to contain inflation by keeping a tight rein on credit. Retail inventories, up 1 percent in September, were of particular concern since an earlier report indicated they could be worse in October. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that retail sales fell a full 1 percent in October, including a 5.1 percent decline in car sales. Manufacturers' inventories, which represent about 45 percent of the total, slipped 0.1 percent and wholesale backlogs, accounting for 25 percent of the total, dropped 0.3 percent. Manufacturers' sales, on the other hand, fell 1.6 percent in September. Retail and wholesale sales both were up 0.7 percent. Overall inventories were 6.4 percent above those of a year ago. Sales increased 6.7 percent over September 1988.
</TEXT>
