reforms are needed if <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> expects to attract investors. `` We say there must be market conditions which make it reasonable to invest there,'' <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> said. But he shied away from stating flatly that a drastic economic overhaul in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> was a pre-condition for financial aid. <PERSON> Volker </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruehe </PERSON>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>, said there were some ways to help <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> soon, including renewal of its telephone communications network and environmental projects. But `` far-reaching changes in the current economic system'' are needed for <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> to be able to attract desperately needed private investment, <PERSON> Ruehe </PERSON> said. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>, a leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION> should not set conditions for its aid. He did say reform must show `` definite signals,'' without explaining what the signals should be. `` We must tell them we are ready to be helpful,'' said <PERSON> Juergen </PERSON> <PERSON> Chrobog </PERSON>, <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>'s chief spokesman. At a news conference earlier in the day, <PERSON> Klein </PERSON> indicated <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> may postpone his summit with East German leaders until the end of December. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> initially said he would meet with <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> German </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <ORGANIZATION> Egon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Krenz </ORGANIZATION> either this month or in 