<HEAD>Nujoma Promises to Protect Individual Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former guerrilla leader who is likely to become <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s first president promised Wednesday to protect individual rights but said he might establish a one-party political system. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON>, leader of the leftist <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, also said he would try to avoid dealings with the white-run government in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, which is ceding control of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> after a 74-year rule And he said English will become the sole official language of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s government and schools, with <LOCATION> Afrikaans </LOCATION> _ the language of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s dominant white group _ losing its official status. <LOCATION> SWAPO </LOCATION>, which began a guerrilla war for independence against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in 1966, was declared the winner Tuesday of United Nations-supervised elections for an assembly that will draft a constitution and declare independence. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> will have 41 of the 72 seats in the assembly, which will convene next week. At least 48 of the 72 members, or two-thirds, must approve decisions by the assembly, and <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> will have to bargain with at least some of the five other parties that won seats. The <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Turnhalle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, a multiracial coalition that favors a capitalist economy, has 21 seats. No other parties won more than four seats. <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> said at a news conference that Namibians would not be pressured to join <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>, but added: `` If the <LOCATION> Namibian </LOCATION> people chose to go one-party and it is done at the polls democratically, it will certainly be so.'' Asked about civil liberties under a SWAPO-led government, he replied: `` Certainly there will be freedom of the press, freedom of assembly, freedom of movement, freedom of association, and there will be also be freedom of religion.'' `` We have no intentions of imposing our views on others and anticipate no serious disagreements,'' <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> said. `` We stand ready to be guided by the democratic principles of open discussion and decision by the majority.'' The last 1,500 South African troops will be withdrawn Nov. 23, said <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Pienaar </PERSON>, the territory's South Africa-installed administrator. Most soldiers left by June, and remaining units have been confined to two northern bases. <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> said his future government would demand that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> surrender control of <LOCATION> Walvis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, a South African enclave which serves as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s only deep-water port. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> says its ownership of <LOCATION> Walvis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> is upheld by international law, but Foreign Minister <PERSON> Pik </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> on Wednesday offered to negotiate terms of usage of the harbor. `` I have always said there are two South Africans: one led by white-minority settlers there _ that one we certainly will not deal with,'' <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> said. `` But we respect non-racial <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> _ that's why we will deal with it.'' <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> wants to declare independence as soon as possible, but <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> declined to set a date. Most observers believe <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> will become independent early next year as long as there are no serious hitches in writing the constitution. During his 30 years in exile, <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON>, 60, and his movement were considered orthodox Marxists. Since <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> leaders began returning to <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> earlier this year, however, they have taken a more moderate approach. <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> favors some government controls on the economy, welcomes foreign investors and wants good relations with East and West. He has repeatedly urged <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s 75,000 whites, and civil servants in particular, to remain in the territory and help develop the emerging nation.
