<HEAD>Abortion Foes Win First Major Statehouse Battle Since `Webster'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-18 pvs `Casey's signature ...' with 12 grafs to
ADD that notification requirement doesn't apply to unmarried women, details
of Missouri ruling, raise reference to penalties against doctors; PICKS
UP 19th graf pvs, `Passage of ...'; DELETES last two grafs to shorten.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BLOOD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Abortion foes today savored their biggest victory since the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> opened the way in July _ the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Legislature's passage of the most restrictive abortion law in the country. `` It's a very bright day for <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s national image,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Beliveau </PERSON>, a leader of the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Pro-Life Federation. `` <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> will stand out as a leader in the nation. This legislation will be seen nationally as reasonable legislation.'' The bill, which bans most abortions after 24 weeks of pregnancy and requires women to inform their husbands before getting an abortion, cleared the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> 33-17 on Tuesday and goes to Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed the bill last month. `` I'm told the bill is in the same form as it was when it left the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said today. `` If that's the case, I'll sign it.'' Abortion-rights advocates, after watching nine attempts to dilute or revise the bill fail, warned that the Legislature was out of step with national sentiment. `` It's a shame, a national disgrace,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Fumo </PERSON>, a Democrat. Some predicted abortion opponents would be voted out of office. `` Having failed to change their minds, we will seriously commit ourselves to changing their faces on Election Day,'' said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Niebrzydowski </PERSON>, president of the state chapter of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> for Women. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> stands to become the first state to enact controls on abortion since the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Webster </LOCATION> vs. Reproductive Health Services opened the way for new curbs. The court upheld a <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> law banning the use of public funds or facilities for abortions and requiring tests after 24 weeks of pregnancy to determine whether the fetus could survive outside the womb. The <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> bill expands on earlier restrictions in banning most abortions in public hospitals. It also bans abortions for the purpose of selecting the baby's sex; prohibits abortions after the 24th week of pregnancy unless the mother faces death or irreversible harm; establishes a 24-hour waiting period after an abortion is requested, and requires women to notify their husbands. An unmarried woman would not have to notify the father. The legislation also would require doctors to inform a woman of the age of the fetus before performing an abortion and explain the risks and alternatives. It also would regulate the medical use of tissue from aborted fetuses. `` What the bill does is put some sensible guidelines into law to try to protect the life of an unborn child,'' said Republican Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Helfrick </PERSON>. `` It does n't prevent abortion, it just restricts it.'' Republican Rep. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Freind </PERSON>, who drafted the bill and guided it through the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` It's a big win; it's a big margin, it's great.'' Freind had said that the bill was designed as a direct challenge to <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> and that he hopes it becomes the vehicle for the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to overturn its 1973 decision establishing the right to an abortion. Passage of the bill puts the pro-choice movement in a quandary, forcing it to decide whether to challenge the law and risk losing <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>. Doctors performing abortions after 24 weeks or because of the sex of the fetus could receive up to seven years in prison and up to $ 15,000 in fines. A husband could seek damages against a doctor who performs an abortion without a form showing that he had been notified. Rep. <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kosinski </PERSON>, a Democratic supporter of the bill, said the bill seeks penalties against doctors because they have `` duties over and above what normal people would have.'' `` The focus is not, absolutely not, on the woman having the abortion,'' he said. The woman should never be penalized for having an abortion.'' <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s Legislature has traditionally been anti-abortion, even though many polls show that most Pennsylvanians are pro-choice. The state has a large rural, conservative population, and both sides agree that the anti-abortion movement has been more efficient politically than the pro-choice side, employing picketing, phone calls and mass mailings. Over the past decade, the Legislature has several times passed restrictions on abortion, but some of the more extreme portions have been struck down by the courts. Passage of the bill comes after a series of victories elsewhere by the abortion-rights side. Two weeks ago, voters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> elected governors with pro-choice positions. A special session of <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> last month ended with lawmakers rejecting every proposal to restrict abortions. Abortion foes in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> abandoned their attempts to get more restrictions passed until next year after a bill stalled last month in a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee. The biggest anti-abortion victory since the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling came last month in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved a bill requiring parental consent for a girl under the age of 18. That proposal is under <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> consideration.
