<HEAD>Bush and House Leaders Agree on Pay Raises and Ethics Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS figure in 3rd graf, The pay, to about $120,700 sted
nearly $125,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> leaders agreed today on a package of congressional pay raises and ethics reforms, clearing the way for swift action before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adjourns next week. `` I am very confident the president will make a statement later today,'' House Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, D-Wash., told reporters The pay plan would bring <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> salaries from $ 89,500 to about $ 120,700 in just over 13 months, and impose new ethics rules on the amount and type of outside income members could earn. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> plan would apply to top officials government-wide, except for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, which was consiering a separate ethics and pay package. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> would get a 7.9 percent raise by Jan. 1, as a `` cost-of-living adjustment'' for the two years since salaries were last increased. A 25 percent raise would take effect a year later, to coincide with the loss in income <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members would suffer when a prohibition takes effect on accepting fees for speeches before interest groups. The bill also would tighten rules for other outside income and gifts, require more disclosure of personal wealth and make other ethics reforms. On Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> counsel <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyden </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> told lawmakers their plan failed to impose enough ethics restrictions on legislative branch officials and their staffs, similar to those governing the executive branch, according to sources who spoke on the condition of anonymity. House Minority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., met with White House Chief of Staff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>