<HEAD>Polowetzky Named Chief Editor of AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Nate </PERSON> <PERSON> Polowetzky </PERSON>, a veteran executive in national and international news operations of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, on Wednesday was named chief editor of <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newsfeatures </ORGANIZATION>, the company's weekend feature service For the past 16 years, <PERSON> Polowetzky </PERSON> has been the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s foreign editor, responsible for foreign news operations around the world. He was given the additional title of assistant general manager in 1977. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boccardi </PERSON>, president and general manager of the news cooperative, said <PERSON> Polowetzky </PERSON> had been a major force in the field of international reporting for many of his 45 years with the company. `` <PERSON> Nate </PERSON>'s broad background and understanding of world events have brought depth to the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s international news coverage,'' <PERSON> Boccardi </PERSON> said. `` I have asked him to return to directing <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newsfeatures </ORGANIZATION> because I know he will bring to that special part of our service the same creativity and breadth of vision.'' <PERSON> Boccardi </PERSON> said the appointment would be effective Jan. 1. As supervising editor of <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newsfeatures </ORGANIZATION>, a post he previously held from 1964 to 1969, <PERSON> Polowetzky </PERSON> will be responsible for that department's in-depth interpretive and other feature productions that move on the national wires primarily for Sunday use. He succeeds <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cappon </PERSON>, 65, who has been given a new assignment to conduct a company-wide campaign on writing and editing for the AP news staff. <PERSON> Polowetzky </PERSON>'s successor as foreign editor will be announced later. <PERSON> Polowetzky </PERSON>, 68, was born and grew up in <LOCATION> Harrison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, and is a journalism graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Rutgers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. He joined the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in 1944, after working for the <ORGANIZATION> Newark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star-Ledger </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>. He spent 12 years as a foreign correspondent in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. He returned to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> from abroad in 1961, and held posts as assistant business news editor, business news editor, assistant general news editor, supervising editor of <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newsfeatures </ORGANIZATION> and enterprise editor before being named to his present position.
