<HEAD>Frank Langella Stars in `Tempest'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> theatergoers have seen so many established actors jump into <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON> and fall flat that failure has become the expectation. Therefore it is with unusual appreciation that one finds <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Langella </PERSON> in `` The Tempest'' playing Prospero with poetry, rich-voiced grandeur and the wisdom accumulated and tempered by a sensitive elder statesman. `` The Tempest'' opened Tuesday night at the off-Broadway Roundabout Theater. <PERSON> Langella </PERSON> does n't carry the play by himself. B.D. <PERSON> Wong </PERSON>, in his next assignment after Broadway's `` M. Butterfly,'' is the spirit Ariel. <PERSON> Wong </PERSON>, wearing only black <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> shorts on his thin frame, looks the epitomy of an other-world sprite. <PERSON> Wong </PERSON>'s Ariel adores <PERSON> Prospero </PERSON> and trusts that <PERSON> Prospero </PERSON> will keep his promise to set him free. <PERSON> Langella </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Prospero </PERSON> who, in the last scene, forgives his enemies, is neither an overbearing father nor a bookish recluse. At the beginning, he talks about his books but acts like a man who has already digested their contents and now is a person of informed action. He loves his daughter, <PERSON> Miranda </PERSON>, and hates to give her up. He makes it clear, though, that he is putting obstacles in her relationship with her swain so their path to happiness wo n't be so easy that they fail to appreciate it. <PERSON> Angela </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherrill </PERSON> has such an unclouded brow and innocent aspect that she looks younger, not older, than <PERSON> Miranda </PERSON>'s 15. <PERSON> Miranda </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON>, son of the King of <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION>, fall in love at first sight. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wittenbauer </PERSON> as <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> seems weak at first, then his voice, as sweet as