<HEAD>Democrat Says Conservatives Stirring Up Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> congressman concerned about continued federal support for the arts said Wednesday that conservatives are stirring up controversy over a few questionable art projects to kill the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION>. `` The right is using <PERSON> Mapplethorpe </PERSON> as their new <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, D-Mont., during a hearing of his Education and <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on postsecondary education <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>, a convicted rapist who committed more crimes after failing to return from a prison furlough in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, was used as an issue in last year's presidntial campaign against <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> banned federal financing of `` obscene'' art and reduced its $ 171 million appropriation for the <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> by $ 45,000 this year after learning that federal funds had helped support two artists, <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mapplethorpe </PERSON>, whose work was considered obscene. That effort was led by Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION>, whose subcommittee is considering legislation to keep the endowment operating, said, `` Those who want to see NEA unfunded are utilizing the unwillingness of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to explain <PERSON> Serrano </PERSON> to get their way.'' He said members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would find it easier to take action against the <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION> than engage in complicated discussions with their constituents about the value of aid that sometimes supports questionable taste. `` The endowment has given out 85,000 grants and run into controversy on 20 of them,'' said <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Garment </PERSON>, an attorney who helped establish the NEA. He said that NEA `` officials and panels have behaved overall with an admirable sense of responsibility.'' <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Fein </PERSON>, an attorney who opposes federal support of art, argued, `` There is no First Amendment right to be subsidized by the government.'' `` Creative art does not need government subsidies to flourish,'' he said. But <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, Garment and attorney <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said government aid attract private donors and government refusal to fund art would lead them away. `` There is a real problem that if corporate <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> begins to think of the arts as tainted, the easy way out is to find something else.''
