<SECOND>PM-Bison Plan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0583,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede HELENA</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with wildlife director briefing congressmen.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>'s hunters and ranchers will be free to kill bison that stray from northern Yellowstone National Park this winter and as many as 200 of the animals might be killed, the state's wildlife director said today. Last year more than 500 <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> bison were killed in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> after they roamed from the park. That was an unprecedented number and prompted outcries from some environmentalists and conservationists. K.L. Cool, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>'s director of fish and game, said the state and officials of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> have agreed that the northern bison herd at Yelowstone should be limited to about 200 to 300 animals, so they can be better managed. Cool and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON>, superintendent of the park, briefed some congressmen as well as environmental and conservation leaders, on the bison management plan. But <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON> told reporters he still has n't determined how the herd will be reduced from the current roughly 400 animals, or how the bison will be kept from roaming onto <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> rangeland this winter. `` On the long haul, trying to herd a buffalo does n't work. <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION> are herded where they want to go,'' said <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON>, adding that efforts will be made to keep the bison in the park by `` gentle hazing'' and whatever else might work. But Cool said the state will maintain its policy of shooting any bison that cross into <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> until the northern <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> herd is reduced to about 200 animals. `` <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> does not want to be viewed as being unrealistic or uncooperative,'' he said. But he said the state legislature has required that hunters be free to shoot the bison that roam into the state. Ranchers have complained vigorously that the buffalo cause damage to property and they fear the animals will transmit brucellosis _ a disease the interferes with reproduction _ to their cattle. Blood tests have shown that more than half of the bison killed in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> last year had brucellosis, he said. Under the <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> plan, bison will be shot in warden-supervised hunts this winter and spring if they leave the park. <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> has about 2,500 bison in three major herds on its more than 2.4 million acres. But only the northern, or <PERSON> Lamar </PERSON>, herd, poses a concern to <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> ranchers. Because of a series of mild winters and other factors, the northern bison herd grew to more than 900 last year and most of them roamed along the <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> into <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> where 569 of the animals were killed. <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> will try to develop ways to better control the size of the northern herd to keep it below 300 animals. But he said ways to do that `` have n't been worked out'' yet. He ruled out the possiblity that hunters would be allowed to hunt the bison within park boundaries. <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, on the park's southern edge, does not allow the shooting of stray bison.
</TEXT>
