3 grafs after 8th, ``The kidnapping...'' to UPDATE with no confirmation
from West German Embassy. ADDS final graf with hostage background information.
No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A previously unknown group calling itself <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Just </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenge </ORGANIZATION> claimed Wednesday it has kidnapped an American and two naturalized West Germans in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The claim came in a typewritten statement delivered to a Western news agency along with photocopies of the passports and visas of the three victims. The American's name was given in the documents as <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Fahrend </PERSON>, 54, of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. The brief Arabic statement said she is a publisher-journalist. The documents identified two Germans as <PERSON> Mounir </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamseddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sami </PERSON>, 39, born in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, and his 7-year-old son <PERSON> Danjel </PERSON>, born in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. The statement said: `` The Organization of Just Revenge announces its responsibility for kidnapping the West German <PERSON> Mounir </PERSON> <PERSON> Sami </PERSON> -LRB- born in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> -RRB- and his son <PERSON> Danjel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sami </PERSON> and American publisher-journalist <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Fahrend </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> for their activities in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>.'' There was no further elaboration in the poorly typed statement, which failed to say when the abduction took place and made no demands. One photocopy showed a visa issued for Ms. <PERSON> Fahrend </PERSON> by the <ORGANIZATION> Lebanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, on Nov. 1 along with an entry stamp by the <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> security department Nov. 3. The two West Germans also entered <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> on Nov. 3 on similar visas, issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Lebanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION> on the same day Ms. <PERSON> Fahrend </PERSON> got hers. The kidnapping claim could not immediately be verified. The American Embassy in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> has been closed since Sept. 22. The West German Embassy in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> said it had no knowledge of the abduction before the statement was released after nightfall. `` But the two victims could be naturalized Germans from <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> descent who are not registered with the embassy in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>,'' said a German official who answered the phone at the embassy. He declined to give his name. Not counting the three people mentioned in the claim, there are 18 foreign hostages being held in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, including eight Americans, four Britons, two West Germans, two Swiss, an Italian and an Irishman. The longest held is <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, 41, chief <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, who was kidnapped March 16, 1985. Most of the hostages are believed held by pro-Iranian extremist factions.
