<HEAD>Poll Finds Americans Ready for War on Garbage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About one in every two Americans believes that garbage disposal problems rank among the three most pressing issues facing local governments, exceeded only by fighting drugs and providing adequate education, according to a survey released Wednesday by the garbage industry. The poll, released by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Solid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Waste </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Managagement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said 52 percent of the people surveyed nationally consider ensuring adequate garbage collection is a serious or extremely serious problem for their local officials. That reflected a higher level of concern about garbage collection than for providing affordable housing or expanding police and fire protection, said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, president of the trade group that represents waste disposal industry. The survey was conducted by <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> Reports and included telephone or face-to-face interviews of 3,000 people during a four-month period this year. There was a 3 percent margin of error. The survey also indicated that public opposition to incinerators that turn garbage into energy is easing in most parts of the country amid increasing worries about finding places to bury solid wastes. It said that 44 percent of those surveyed nationwide said they would favor locating such incinerator plants in their area, 8 percentage points higher than those reponding similarly in a poll a year earlier. Thirty-six percent of the people opposed such plants and 20 percent said they did n't know. Opposition to burning garbage continued to be greatest in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, where a new waste-to-energy plant was favored by only 36 percent of those surveyed, compared to 42 percent who opposed. Even in that region, however, those who favored a plant incrased by 5 percentage points compared to the 1988 survey. The Northeast, however, had the largest percentage of people, 67 percent of those surveyed, who considered garbage collection as a serious or extremely serious issue facing local governments, ranking only behind the battle to curb drug abuse. Garbage collection issues were found to be of the least concern in the central part of the country, where it ranked last among five areas of concern with only 37 percent of the people saying they considered it a serious local problem. In other findings, the poll indicated an increased interest in recycling programs, but it said the public no longer considers recycling `` a simple ` magic bullet' solution'' to the disposal of waste products, said <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, the trade group's president. Two-thirds of those surveyed said they had participated in recycling cans, bottles or papers and 44 percent said they would buy products containing recycled materials if given a choice, according to the survey. In a related report, the trade group said that as of the end of September, 38 states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> have enacted some form of waste recycling laws, although in many cases the full requirements do not go into effect until the early to mid-1990s.
