<HEAD>Derwinski Promises Rural Hospitals in Sparsely Populated Areas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Veterans Secretary <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> pledged Wednesday that rural VA hospitals in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and other sparsely populated areas will remain open despite budgetary constraints. `` I have no intention of closing and no intention of making changes that in any way would diminish hospital care in rural areas,'' <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` These kinds of locations must stay.'' <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> testified at a hearing into the delivery of health care to rural veterans. Other witnesses and western state senators complained that rural veterans suffer from a lack of medical personnel, a lack of access to health care facilities and a lack of resources at the rural hospitals since most are unaffiliated with medical schools. Sen. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON>, D-Mont., complained that policy makers in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> are fundamentally oblivious to the needs of rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> `` They really do n't understand the sense of space and distance,'' he said. Although 95 percent of all veterans live within a 100-mile radius of the nearest VA facility, according to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legion </ORGANIZATION>, in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> 83 percent of the veterans served by the <LOCATION> Miles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> hospital live more than 100 miles from it. <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON> noted that <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> has nine centers compared with two in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> noted that in his native <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> three hospitals were within six miles from one another. Sen. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daschle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.D. </LOCATION>, complained that veterans with non-service-connected disabilities and incomes above $ 16,500 if single or $ 20,000 if married are being denied VA care because of service cutbacks over the last five years. Those `` Class B'' and `` Class C'' veterans are generally provided care when resources are available. The poorer and service-connected disabled _ `` Class A'' _ receive first-priority care. Dr. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Winship </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION>'s medical division said there was no policy decision to cut out the B and C patients. He said the demand for care by Category A patients has `` virtually consumed'' the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION>'s resources.
