<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Gate     11-15 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Gate,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>200-Year-Old Gate Again a Stage for History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The battle-scarred sandstone columns of the Brandenburg Gate, which were the backdrop for <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s last stand and a workers' uprising against Communism in 1953, once again tower over the stage of history. The 200-year-old gate, <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s most famous landmark, has stood as the symbol of German division for 28 years. With the Berlin Wall quickly crumbling, the gate is being called the symbol of German unity. It also has been the backdrop for much of the television coverage beamed around the world in the past week of fast-moving developments. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has said it is considering opening a <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall border crossing at the <LOCATION> Brandenburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gate </LOCATION>. There was wide speculation in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> that an opening would be knocked through the wall Thursday, although there was no official confirmation. The gate _ the size of a five-story building _ remained on the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> side when the Berlin Wall was built in 1961. The famous Unten den <PERSON> Linden </PERSON> boulevard ends at the gate. On the Western side, the sprawling avenue that leads to the gate was renamed June 17 Street, after the date of the workers' uprising in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> in 1953 that was bloodily crushed by Soviet tanks. <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> workers, angered by the nationalization and collectivization policies of the Communist government, began their street demonstrations at the Brandenburg Gate and tore down the red flag from the top of the gate. In the closing days of World War II, Soviet tanks rumbled by the gate as they closed in on <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s bunker in the chancellery. Only a few hundred yards away was the heart of <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s government in a small complex on <LOCATION> Wilhelmstrasse </LOCATION>, which also served as the seat of the imperial government. The Reichstag also is not far away. The Brandenburg Gate also marked <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s rise to power. Nazi brown shirts staged a triumphant torch parade through the gate when <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> was named chancellor on Jan. 30, 1933. Built from 1788 to 1791 by <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Gotthard </PERSON> <PERSON> Langhans </PERSON>, the six-column gate was commissioned by Prussian King <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilhelm </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>. When it was built, it opened the road to the region of <LOCATION> Brandenburg </LOCATION>, getting its name. The gate was modeled after the Acropolis in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> to reflect the king's intention to make <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> a city of learning and arts. On top of the gate is a bronze chariot with the goddess <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON>. It was hauled away to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> when <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> defeated the Prussians at <PERSON> Jena </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Auerstadt </LOCATION> on Oct. 27, 1806. He marched into <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> through the Brandenburg Gate. The chariot was brought back to <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> after <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON>'s defeat in 1814. After the Franco-German war in 1870-71, the victorious Prussians made a triumphal return to <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, the new imperial capital, again through the <LOCATION> Brandenburg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gate </LOCATION>. The gate was heavily damaged in the last days of World War II and marked the border between the Soviet and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> sectors of conquered <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. It was restored between 1956 and 1958. The chariot was repaired and paid for by <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> under Mayor <PERSON> Willy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandt </PERSON>, but <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> authorities removed the Prussian eagle and the iron cross from <LOCATION> Victoria </LOCATION>'s staff before mounting it again. In 1963, Communist soldiers dropped huge red drapes over the gate to prevent President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> from looking into <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> when he visited <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> and delivered his `` Ich bin ein Berliner'' speech. The gate, the last of the 20 gates to <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> still standing, is 66 feet high, 215 feet wide and 36 feet deep.
</TEXT>
