<HEAD>Bush Urged to Meet With Allies Before _ Not After _ Gorbachev Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> should meet with the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies before _ not after _ his summit next month with President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, the head of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s legislative arm said Wednesday. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, said it was `` unthinkable'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would meet with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> without first consulting the other members of the 16-nation <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON>, a member of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION>, said the agenda for the Dec. 2-3 shipboard meeting off the island of <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> was likely to be dominated by the dramatic changes in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, particularly in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> sources, who demanded anonymity, said a senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official will meet with the allies in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> on Dec. 4 to discuss the summit, but it was not yet certain who that would be. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, administration officials have said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was considering calling a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> summit in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> after the <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> meeting to discuss new political and military strategy for the West. The <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> sources said contingency plans were being made for such a presidential visit. French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> hurriedly scheduled a meeting Saturday of all 12 leaders of the European Community, the Common Market trading bloc, to discuss Eastern <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Some analysts believe the move was designed to give the community leaders a chance to discuss the developments before the <LOCATION> Bush-Gorbachev </LOCATION> summit. <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> reminded <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> that the political atmosphere in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> was sensitive. `` There is a great joy and genuine emotion, but there is also a good deal of confusion and concern about where this process will eventually take us,'' he said. `` It is absolutely imperative,'' he said, `` that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> president demonstrates a true awareness of the current situation by offering reassurance and predictability to the <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> allies.'' He said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has `` a special responsibility and the international situation demands nothing less than he meet this responsibility.'' <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> cautioned against a replay of the 1986 summit at <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, between President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, which turned into a much more ambitious meeting than had been expected. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> arrived with sweeping arms control proposals that caught the Americans off guard. The allies were furious such discussions took place without consultations. `` Politicians of every stripe in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are agreed there must be no more Yaltas or Reykjaviks,'' <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> said. `` The present system would be unable to contain a repetition along these lines.'' <LOCATION> Yalta </LOCATION> refers to the controversial 1945 meeting of President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>, Soviet leader <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON> at which the shape of post-war <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> was determined. The <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> is made up of legislators of the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> nations.
