<HEAD>Yellowstone Trying to Keep its Bison From Harm's Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it will try to keep the bison herd in northern Yellowstone National Park from roaming into <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, but conceded as many as 200 of the animals may be shot this winter if they enter the state. The killing of nearly 600 <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> buffalo by <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> ranchers and hunters last winter and spring prompted sharp criticism from environmentalists and conservationists. K.L. Cool, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>'s wildlife director, said Wednesday the state is trying to av300 animals, so that they can be better managed and kept out of <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> rangeland. Cool and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON>, superintendent of the park, briefed some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> as well as environmental and conservation leaders, on the bison management plan. But they conceded they have n't figured out how the huge animals will be kept from roaming out of the park, or how the size of the herd will be reduced. `` On the long haul, trying to herd a buffalo does n't work. <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION> are herded where they want to go,'' said <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON>, adding that efforts will be made to keep the bison in the park by `` gentle hazing'' and whatever else might work. Cool said the state will maintain its policy of shooting any bison that cross onto <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> state lands until the northern <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> herd is reduced to about 200 animals. Hunters and ranchers will be given license to shoot the animals under supervision from a game warden, he said. `` <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> does not want to be viewed as being unrealistic or uncooperative,'' he said. But he said the state legislature has required that hunters be free to shoot the bison that roam into the state. Ranchers have complained vigorously that the buffalo cause damage to property and they fear that they will transmit brucellosis _ a disease the interferes with reproduction _ to their cattle. Blood tests have shown that more than half of the bison killed in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> last year had brucellosis, he said. Most of the vast, federally-owned <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> park lies in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> but its northern end extends into <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> does not allow the shooting of stray bison. <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> has about 2,500 bison in three major herds on its more than 2.4 million acres. But only the northern, or <PERSON> Lamar </PERSON>, herd, poses a concern to <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> ranchers. Because of a series of mild winters and other factors, the northern bison herd grew to more than 900 last year year and most of them roamed along the <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> into <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, where 569 of the animals were killed last winter and spring. That number was unprecedented and prompted criticism from conservationists and environmentalists. Buffalo have roamed onto <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> lands for years, but not nearly in the numbers that left the park last winter. According to <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> officials, 190 <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> buffalos were killed in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> in 1984 through 1988. <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> will try to develop ways to better control the size of the northern herd to keep it below 300 animals. But he said ways to do that `` have n't been worked out.'' He ruled out the possiblity that hunters would be allowed to hunt the bison within park boundaries.
