<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Through what was called `` a miracle of international cooperation,'' three of four fingers were reattached to a Polish sailor's hand, more than two days after they were severed in a shipboard accident. Dr. <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chow </PERSON>, director of replantation and chief of the microvascular surgery team at the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday the fingers were not reattached to the hand of <PERSON> Zbyskyo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kajowski </PERSON> for more than 54 hours. This appears to be a record because the longest time previously known between this type of accident and reattachment was 39 hours, said <PERSON> Chow </PERSON>, who coordinated the surgery. The accident occurred aboard the Greek freighter, SS Success, on Nov. 6 some 500 miles off <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> when <PERSON> Kajowski </PERSON>'s hand was caught under falling machinery, doctors said. <PERSON> Kajowski </PERSON>, 39, suffered what <PERSON> Chow </PERSON> characterized as `` a severe crush-amputation'' injury that severed the four fingers of the left hand where they meet the palm. The ship captain received emergency advice from Dr. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultze </PERSON>, head of the emergency room at <ORGANIZATION> King </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> VII </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>. That included immersion of the digits in a saline solution and keep them cool but not frozen. Paramedics on the ship gave <PERSON> Kajowski </PERSON> emergency first-aid and doctors on <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION> contacted the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, which called <LOCATION> Chow </LOCATION>, the doctor said. `` Right then time was important,'' <PERSON> Chow </PERSON> said. `` The ship was t