<HEAD>`White Supremacy Monument' Moved From Canal Street</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 20-foot obelisk known as the white supremacy monument was taken apart and moved Wednesday from the foot of Canal Street to a warehouse. The Streets Department says the monument, erected in 1891 to commemorate a white uprising which overthrew the Reconstruction government in 1874, is being moved on advice of engineers for traffic improvements. The National Association for the Advancement of White People, which founder and former <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION> imperial wizard <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> calls a white civil rights group, initially objected to moving it. It is inscribed with the names of 16 members of the White League who died in the 18-minute battle. An inscription praising white supremacy was added in 1932, and white supremacy groups have rallied near the monument for decades. The <ORGANIZATION> NAAWP </ORGANIZATION> complained to state and national preservation officials, who worked out an agreement under which the city may store the monument for 18 months, but must put it back up by May 1, 1991, within two blocks of the original site.
