<TEXT>
 Sheriff's deputies posing as students spent six months in high schools looking for drug use, but came up empty-handed. `` It's great news,'' <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Douglas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> schools spokeswoman, said Tuesday. `` It really gives a strong picture of the teachers and administrators and the kids.'' Sheriff's Lt. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said the operation was planned in August 1988 after a school district survey showed an alarmingly high amount of drug use by young people outside the schools. The sheriff recruited an undisclosed number of officers to mingle with students in the county's three high schools last spring and this fall. The officers fooled students and teachers, by doing homework, going to football games and hanging out with students. But they failed to make a single drug purchase, officials said. `` We're not denying there's a drug problem, but we're saying we're being successful at keeping it out of the schools,'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said. `` It shows a lot of the drug education and concern by the schools and the sheriff's department is starting to pay off.''
