<HEAD>Public Believes Political Bias Growing in News Media</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 8 grafs for grafs 3-9 pvs, Among network ... 11 percent,
using only figures for top two categories of believability for sake of
clarity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Increasingly, the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> public has come to believe there is political bias in news coverage, a new survey finds. Despite that _ and a belief by 63 percent of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> public that news organizations fuel controversies _ a favorable view of those organizations is expressed by 82 percent for network TV news, 80 percent for local television news and 77 percent for daily newspapers, said the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> survey released Wednesday. Among network big names, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> news </ORGANIZATION> anchor <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> `` is now the most highly regarded of the television correspondents,'' according to the poll. While his believability rating topped his network rivals, it dropped five points from its 1985 level. CBS' <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rather </PERSON> lost 10 believability points, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Koppel </PERSON> 9 points, and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Brokaw </PERSON> 7 points At the other end of the believability scale was <PERSON> Geraldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> whose rating dropped 48 points between the two surveys. The survey, conducted among members of the public, media, government, academia and business, is the first work of the Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; The Press. `` Believability is down, there's just no question about it,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, an associate professor of government at <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and associate director of the survey. `` On the average, news organizations lost nine points on a sale of 100 in terms of believability,'' he said. The survey's rating scale includes four categories ranging from the top -LRB- you can believe all or most of what the person says -RRB- to the bottom -LRB- believe almost nothing -RRB-. Counting the percentages of respondents ranking news people or organizations in the top two categories, the top of the list reads: <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> 85 percent, <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> 84 percent, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> 83 percent, <PERSON> Brokaw </PERSON> 81 percent and Rather and <PERSON> Koppel </PERSON> 79 percent. At the bottom is <PERSON> Rivera </PERSON> at 26 percent. Other names and organizations include <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> at 75 percent, The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> 74 percent, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Donaldson </PERSON> 71, <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION> 70, and columnist <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Will </PERSON> 59. By comparison, Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> gets a rating of 70 percent, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> 63 percent, former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> 47, <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> 33, Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> 29 and businessman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> 25. `` The most interesting case, bar none for me, is <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. `` <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> is the only news organization that has sustained no decrease in believability.'' The reason, he said, is that <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> concentrates on hard news. `` It does n't do a lot of interpretation, does n't do a lot of watchdoggery, it just shows hard news, particularly the sort of news the public is most interested in.'' The Los Angeles-based <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s holdings include the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Newsday </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> Sun. It also includes a cable television division. Pollsters said that since <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mirror </ORGANIZATION> began its research program five years ago, there has been a `` significant erosion of public confidence in the press as an objective reporter of the news and as an impartial observer of the political and social scene.'' In 1985, 53 percent of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> public believed news media favored one side in dealing with social and political issues. That percentage remained in the 50s in five subsequent surveys and rose to 68 percent in the current one. Similarly those who believe news organizations `` deal fairly with all sides'' dropped from 34 percent to 28 percent. When the press respondents were asked whether news organizations merely report the news or fuel controversies by their coverage, 46 percent opted for the first and 49 percent for the second. `` Drive controversy'' also got the nod from 75 percent of the academics, 80 percent of business leaders and 77 percent of government leaders. Not surprisingly, members of the news media _ 81 percent _ said they cover stories about the personal and ethical behavior of politicians very or fairly responsibly. Only 68 percent of the general public and 60 percent of government leaders agreed. The percentage of people who think news organizations get their facts straight rose to 54 percent from a low of 40 percent a year ago. And there was a slight increase in the percentage of those who believe the press respects people's privacy _ from 14 percent last year to 23 percent. The survey found that the media consistently overstate interest in news stories. In eight of nine stories cited, the media thought the public was more interested than the public said it was. The greatest overstatements of public interest were on stories about <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, the <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Tyson-Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Givens </PERSON> divorce and former <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, the survey said. News about the scandal at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> was the only instance in which the press correctly gauged the very low level of public interest. Sixty-four percent of the members of the public surveyed said they read a newspaper nearly every day, while 67 percent said they regularly watched a network news show. A total of 508 media telephone interviews were conducted Aug. 3-Sept. 29, while 275 interviews were conducted with leaders in business, government and academia Aug. 3-Oct. Nearly 100 interviews were conducted with government leaders, including 38 members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, 12 senaors, nine governors, 21 mayors and 16 senior <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials. There were 100 interviews with presidents and journalism deans at major colleges and universities. The Gallup Organization conducted a telephone survey of 1,507 adult members of the public Aug. 9-28. The margin of error ranged from 3 percentage points for the largest sample to 11 percentage points for the smallest.
