<HEAD>Petitions Filed to Allow Competition in Local Telephone Access Services</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to clarify that other local companies also provide
this service; INSERTS three grafs after 8th graf bgng: ``Metropolitan Fiber
xxx to UPDATE with BellSouth and NYNEX comments, </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fiber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> announced Wednesday it has filed petitions with the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to allow alternative telecommunications carriers to compete for local telephone access services. `` This action is a logical extension of historical regulatory policy designed to generate competition in the telecommunications industry,'' said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pompliano </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> MFS </ORGANIZATION>, which is based in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Oakbrook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Terrace </LOCATION>, Ill. Currently the regional <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> and other operating companies provide local phone access for all long-distance carriers. Nearly 50 cents of every dollar spent on long-distance services goes to the Bell companies for access fees, totaling about $ 20 billion a year. <PERSON> Pompliano </PERSON> said his company was asking the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> `` to enforce the Modified Final Judgment to require that local access ... be ` unbundled' to the fullest extent possible to permit fair and equitable competition.'' Also, he said, `` we are asking the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> to mandate that alternative local telecommunications carriers can cost-effectively interconnect'' and locate equipment at <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> facilities. `` That means <ORGANIZATION> MFS </ORGANIZATION> and similar alternative carriers can install their equipment in Bell-owned switch sites and hook up to the user community via the Bell network,'' <PERSON> Pompliano </PERSON> said. Commenting on the announcement, A. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> senior vice president for external affairs, said: `` Metropolitan Fiber is free to use <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION>'s services any way it wants, and it is free to connect its own network with <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION>'s.'' `` Metropolitan Fiber, however, is demanding more than this. It is demanding collocation, which is, in effect, the ability to set up their shop in our store. <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> has no legal obligation to do this, but it has agreed to meet a number of Metropolitan's requests,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> McCloskey </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> BellSouth </ORGANIZATION>, said about the <ORGANIZATION> MFS </ORGANIZATION> action: `` These petitions appear to propose more confusion in the telephone industry. They do not appear to offer any new services that residential customers might use'' but instead appear `` designed to benefit only high-volume users of specialized business services.'' <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Jasinski </PERSON>, public relations manager for <ORGANIZATION> NYNEX </ORGANIZATION>, commented: `` The announcement by Metropolitan Fiber Systems simply confirms the fact that there's growing competition in the telecommunications markets served by the regional holding companies.'' He added that `` <ORGANIZATION> NYNEX </ORGANIZATION> stands ready to consider any reasonable requests for interconnection that will help ensure customer demands are met.'' <ORGANIZATION> MFS </ORGANIZATION> currently operates fiber optic communication networks in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, with networks in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> to be completed by the end of this year. The company also is planning to construct networks in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Pompliano </PERSON> said `` the problem with having a single supplier exclusively control the local access business is that the lack of competition provides no incentive to be responsive to customer needs, offer new services, or lower rates.'' `` If alternative local telecommunications carriers like <ORGANIZATION> MFS </ORGANIZATION> are allowed to offer access services, technology will improve ahead of current projections and the rates for local access will drop,'' the <ORGANIZATION> MFS </ORGANIZATION> chief said.
