<TEXT>
 New windows with thick bullet-proof glass were installed in Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s office last week as part of efforts to tighten his security, officials said Wednesday. The replacement of existing windows with bullet-proof glass, completed last week, cost $ 73,000, the department said. Security for the attorney general has been noticeably tighter since <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s crackdown on drug lords, which prompted threats from cocaine traffickers to kill <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. The attorney general now travels in an armor-plated limousine that cost more than $ 100,000. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> no longer uses the public entrance to his office at the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, leaving instead by a variety of routes. The handful of <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents in <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s security detail have recently been spotted carrying gun cases, indicated they are now armed with high-powered weapons.
