<HEAD>Bill Would Force States To Suspend Driver's Licenses Of Drug Abusers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The top federal highway official asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday not to pass a bill that would compel states to suspend driver's licenses of convicted drug abusers. Federal Highway Administrator <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> asked a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee to defer action on the proposal until more is known about its legal implications. The bill would withhold a portion of federal highway funds from states that do not pass such laws. Sen. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Symms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>, called the measure `` legalized blackmail'' and said it would unduly extend the reach of the federal government. But <PERSON> Symms </PERSON> later said he was keeping an open mind because of his support for the goals of the bill. Its chief sponsor, Sen. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, said the measure would discourage drug use, particularly among young people, and make highways safer. `` Driving is a privilege, not a right,'' <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON> said. `` And if a citizen chooses to engage in illegal drug behavior, he or she should lose that privilege.'' <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> said about half the states already have laws that allow suspension or revokation of driving privileges upon conviction for a drug offense, although most do not make such action mandatory. He said a law that suspends a driver's license for sex offenses was thrown out by the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Some states have had difficulty tracking down drivers to obtain their suspended licenses, particularly in large urban areas, <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> said. `` While we support the goals of the program,'' <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> said, `` we believe that more time may be helpful to consider the many complex issues involved.'' Lt. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> police officer speaking for the <ORGANIZATION> Fraternal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Order </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>, said the group supports the bill but has reservations about its possible impact in states where the loss of federal funds might affect money going to police departments. He said rules are needed to prevent this. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perretti </PERSON> said state officials believe their law that suspends driver's licenses has discouraged drug use among youths and middle-class offenders. `` Suspension of a driver's license is the most effective deterent next to jail,'' <PERSON> Perretti </PERSON> told the subcommittee.
</TEXT>
