<HEAD>IRA Bomb Blows Up Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bomb ripped through a car traveling on a rural highway in <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tyrone </LOCATION> Wednesday, killing the driver, police said. The <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> claimed responsibility in a statement issued to local media and alleged that the victim, a businessman, worked for the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> province's security forces. Police denied he had any connection with the security forces. The man, whose name was not released, was driving on the highway between <LOCATION> Dungannon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ballygawley </LOCATION>, about 8 miles from the province's border with the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, when a 2-pound bomb hidden under the car detonated, a police spokesman said. The explosion blew the roof off the car, which burst into flames, the spokesman said. He spoke on condition of anonymity. The <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> is fighting to drive the British out of <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and unite the Protestant-dominated province with the overwhelmingly Roman Catholic Irish Republic. Earlier, several hundred <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> demonstrators marked the fourth anniversary of the signing of the Anglo-Irish agreement by linking hands along main roads in different parts of the province. Organizers had predicted a turnout of 300,000 people. `` I recognize that the imaginative scheme did not capture the imagination of the Ulster people,'' said an organizer, the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Smyth </PERSON>, a legislator in the British <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. Organizers blamed the low turnout partly on the absence of two <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> leaders, the Rev. <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Paisley </PERSON> who is visiting <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Molyneaux </PERSON> who was lobbying fellow British legislators in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The 1985 agreement between <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> gave the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> government a consultative role in the affairs of <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> for the first time. It set up a permanent secretariat of <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> civil servants in <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> to deal with the grievances the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> minority claim they suffer under the <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> majority. The agreement also pledged cooperation between the two countries on security measures along their common border.
