<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cabinet ministers made plans Wednesday for bringing order to the return of about 3,000 Egyptian workers a day from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and an official said they leaving for economic reasons, not because of maltreatment. In <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> called a meeting of Egyptian residents and complained about <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> newspaper reports that the workers were being mistreated. He promised to investigate any complaints, but discounted claims that many Egyptians have been killed maliciously in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. He said they died naturally or from violence in numbers understandable in a group of about 2 million people. Rumors circulated Wednesday among diplomats in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> that <PERSON> Nabil </PERSON> <PERSON> Najm </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> ambassador, had received a death threat. Embassy spokesman <PERSON> Daoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Farhan </PERSON> denied the reports and said the ambassador was not in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Radwan </PERSON>, secretary-general of President <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON>'s cabinet, said the ministers were told the main reason Egyptians were returning was that new fiscal rules in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> reduced the amount of money alien workers could send home He said <PERSON> Ibrahim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ouf </PERSON>, Egyptian ambassador in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, told the ministers a manpower surplus had resulted from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s demobilization after the truce agreement of August 1988 in the 8-year-old war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> Ouf said Iraqi employers were dismissing Egyptians and giving their jobs to former <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> soldiers, according to <PERSON> Radwan </PERSON>. The Cabinet official did not address reports by the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Al-Akhbar </ORGANIZATION> that more than 100 Egyptian corpses were returned from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in October, compared to an average of two or three in other months. He did say, however, that Ouf told the ministers Iraqi authorities were prepared to present complete files on Egyptians who die in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Al-Akhbar </ORGANIZATION> has reported that <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> death certificates attributed most of the Egyptian deaths to violent causes. On Wednesday, it said five bodies of Egyptian men aged 23-40 arrived at the <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> airport the day before with documents indicating two died of skull fractures, one of burns and one of heart failure. <ORGANIZATION> Al-Akhbar </ORGANIZATION> said the cause of the fifth death was not determined. <PERSON> Radwan </PERSON>'s comments were distributed by the official <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. He said the ministerial group was headed by Prime Minister <PERSON> Atef </PERSON> <PERSON> Sedki </PERSON> and including the foreign, finance, labor, immigration, supplies and administrative affairs ministers, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> and Ambassador Ouf. Tens of thousands of Egyptians are said to be awaiting transportation from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The departures began soon after <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> issued new regulations Oct. 1 on sending money home. <PERSON> Sedki </PERSON> and <PERSON> Taha </PERSON> <PERSON> Yassin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramadan </PERSON>, deputy prime minister, are to discuss the situation Saturday in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>. Authorities at <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> airport said 25,000-27 ,000 Egyptian workers arrived past week on Egyptian and Iraqi airliners They said both airlines had increased their number of flights to handle the traffic.
