<ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest cigarette maker, a part of the official <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION> bicentennial celebration of the Bill of Rights. In a `` memorandum of understanding'' <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> agreed to donate $ 600,000 to the Archives trust fund in exchange for being allowed to publish or broadcast announcements and promotional materials commemorating the bicentennial and referring to the Archives. Critics have questioned whether the broadcast announcements constitute cigarette advertisements on radio and television, which was banned by the federal government in 1971. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> ads are running on television and do not contain any health warning and apparently are a fragrant violation of the law prohibiting such video commercials,'' said <PERSON> Luken </PERSON>. <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>' vice president of corporate affairs, said he did n't believe the company's announcements violated the advertising ban since `` there is no cigarette called <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>.'' `` In the same week that the Berlin Wall is being torn down that people in this country are being criticized for celebrating the Bill of Rights is very strange,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> added in a reference to recent events in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The company plans to continue the campaign and send a representative to testify at Thursday's hearing, he said. Critics also have questioned corporate sponsorship of Archives programs. <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, criticized the `` commercialization of space in the building which houses the symbols of our nation.'' <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> not only permitted the agency to accept tax-exempt donations to its trust fund but also specifically `` encouraged it to do so in order to enhance it's archival and outreach activities,'' said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the Archives. While this the first large corporate donation to the Archives trust fund, <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> said, it is not the first cooperative effort with private industry. In addition, she said <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>' sponsorship of an exhibit in the Archives building is no different than when other companies underwrote receptions to celebrate the bicentenial of the Constitution or when <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> itself sponsored exhibits at the National Art Gallery.
