<HEAD>Atlantic Fleet Prepares for Two-day Safety Stand-down</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NK2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.W. PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s top safety officer on Wednesday compared a two-day safety stand-down to a timeout in an athletic contest called to `` review the game plan and get back to the basics.'' The exercise is a useful tool, said Capt. <PERSON> Ferguson </PERSON> <PERSON> Norton </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. The stand-down ordered Tuesday is the most widespread in memory, he said. It was ordered after a rash of 10 accidents in the last three weeks killed 10 people and injured 71. All <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> units will spend 48 of 72 hours this week reviewing procedures and training, looking at the work environment, and reminding all hands of safety measures, according to the stand-down ordered by Secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and Adm. <PERSON> Carlisle </PERSON> <PERSON> A.H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Trost </PERSON>, chief of naval operations. `` A timeout also can be called to halt the momentum of the opponent, ... in this case, the string of mishaps,'' <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> said at a news conference. The safety center analyzes all <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> accidents worldwide in an attempt to prevent further problems. `` Safety is the product of sound operating procedures and good training,'' <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> said. `` We want to leave no stone unturned to ensure that safety is uppermost in the minds of all hands, at all times,'' said Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s record of safety has been steadily improving over recent years. There were 118 major problems during operations in 1984. That figure has dropped to 69 so far this year, according to <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> figures. However, the number of fatalities for 1984 was 64; 102 sailors have been killed so far this year, including 47 in the April 19th gun turret explosion aboard the battleship USS Iowa. <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> said the center's analysis found no clear links between accidents of the last three weeks. He also said there was no indication that <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget cuts had any effect on accidents. `` We're got a tough business. ... We're expected to be able to go tomorrow anywhere in the world and be an instrument of national policy. That's what the government expects and that's what the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people expect,'' <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, personnel at the <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> spent the day preparing for the stand-down. `` Most of the units did not find out about the stand-down until late yesterday. The 72-hour window gives them time to plan the rotations and wind down any missions they are on,'' <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION> ships at sea will not be called home for the safety drill. `` Ships at sea will stand-down at sea. Those on shore will do their stand-down there.'' The most serious of the recent accidents occurred Oct. 29 when a jet pilot making his first landing on an aircraft carrier crashed into the <LOCATION> USS </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> in the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. he pilot and four others were killed. On Monday, the destroyer USS Kinkaid and a freighter collided in the <LOCATION> Malacca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> killing one <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> crewman, injuring five, and starting fires on both vessels. Last Thursday, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> reserve pilot flying an A-7E jet crashed into an apartment complex in <LOCATION> Smyrna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, killing two civilians and injuring two others, including himself.
