<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of Colombian judges and court workers ended a two-week strike Wednesday after the government promised to increase security for judges threatened by drug traffickers. Justice Minister <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON> said in a meeting with union representatives that beginning next week, the government would start providing the judges with bulletproof vests, armored cars and bodyguards, a union representative said. The strike by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> involved about 5,000 judges and 12,000 court workers. <PERSON> Salazar </PERSON> also pledged that the offices of certain judges would be moved to government buildings offering more security, said <PERSON> Consuelo </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrera </PERSON>, a union board member. `` Some judges' offices are located in extremely dangerous neighborhoods,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Herrera </PERSON> said. `` These are the ones that will be moved.'' She said the union was satisfied with the government's promises but that their quick implementation was vital to keeping the courts open. `` If the government does not act quickly to put the measures in place, the union will call another strike,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Herrera </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. The judges say the measures are necessary to prevent the decimation of their ranks by drug traffickers retaliating for a government crackdown on the country's cocaine cartels. The latest strike began Nov. 2, one day after a federal judge was shot and killed in <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION>, the hub of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s cocaine trade. No one claimed responsibility for the killing, but authorities have blamed traffickers. Three judges have been killed in the last three months, all presumably by drug traffickers. President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON>