<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A non-communist Cambodian rebel leader said Wednesday the men who led the brutal <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> government more than a decade ago should accept exile in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to quiet fears that they will return to power. Son <PERSON> Sann </PERSON>, whose guerrillas are technically allied with the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, addressed a news conference on the first day of the annual <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> debate on <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. `` I invite <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON> and all other <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> leaders who committed great crimes to prepare for their future in a pagoda in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' he said. He referred to reports that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, embarrassed by <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON>'s record, would offer him and his colleagues refuge, thus eliminating a major obstacle to a Cambodian settlement `` If you disarm and <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> and all parties and let people vote, they are not going to vote for the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Son </PERSON> <PERSON> Sann </PERSON> told the reporters. <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON> led the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> government that took over <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in April 1975 and killed or starved hundreds of thousands of Cambodians before it was ousted by the Vietnamese invasion of December 1978. The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> now is the strongest fighting force in the alliance of three guerrilla groups. Addressing the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZA