<HEAD>U.N. Passes 1st Joint US-Soviet `Peace and Security' Resolution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday passed an unprecedented joint U.S.-Soviet resolution urging nations to settle conflicts peacefully and respect human rights. Although the resolution passed unanimously, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> expressed unease over whether the superpowers might use their new spirit of cooperation to stifle debate on issues not high on their agenda. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s Ambassador <PERSON> Hideo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kagami </PERSON> said: `` Any part of this resolution must not be interpreted to justify undue politicization of issues of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> under the name of peace and security.'' <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s Ambassador <PERSON> Paulo </PERSON> <PERSON> Nogueira-Batista </PERSON> pointed out that the resolution stressed the role of the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, but failed to mention the Economic and <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which sets policy on social matters such as the environment, AIDS, and the anti-drug fight. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> both joined in the consensus on the resolution, however. The resolution urges all nations to obey the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Charter and use <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> bodies to settle disputes, but offers no specific proposals to end conflicts in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> or elsewhere. It calls on all nations to `` respect the principles of sovereign equality, political independence and territorial integrity of states, and non-intervention in foreign affairs.'' It also calls on nations to `` refrain from the threat or use of force inconsistent with the charter,'' which permits only self-defense, and to `` peacefully settle disputes.'' Nations should `` adhere to the principles of equal rights and self-determination of peoples, respect for human rights and fundamental freedoms, cooperation among states.'' General Assembly resolutions have no binding effect on nations, but the superpowers have the ability to persuade their allies to resolve disputes peacefully when they wish. Earlier this month, at a joint U.S.-Soviet news conference, Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> stressed that the resolution puts an end to the superpower rivalry that prevailed during the Cold War years. `` Today, it is an end to confrontation,'' said his Soviet counterpart, <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrovsky </PERSON>.
