<HEAD>Ten-Fold Increase In Potential Losses To Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 10-fold expansion of federal loan programs over the past 13 years now means the government has lent, guaranteed or insured $ 5 trillion _ $ 20,000 for every man, woman and child in the country, congressional auditors said Wednesday. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said ultimate losses to the government would not reach that level. `` While the government will undoubtedly not be required to provide financial assistance for its total exposure associated with these programs, its continuing and growing exposure to losses can not be ignored,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. While huge losses already have manifested themselves in the farm credit bailout in 1987 and the savings and loan rescue this year, the government is experiencing billions of dollars in losses from other credit and insurance programs as well, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said. Altogether, the wide variety of loan guarantee programs has increased by 51 percent over the past five years to $ 550 billion. But annual defaults on those guarantees have jumped 138 percent, from $ 4.7 billion in 1983 to $ 11.2 billion last year, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. The real situation could be worse, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> cautioned. For example, just two months ago <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> auditors found $ 4.2 billion in <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> loan defaults in 1988 _ five times what the agency reported. `` The full magnitude of the government's losses under its credit assistance and insurance programs is not known,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Because of long-standing deficiencies in financial managements and inconsistencies in the application of accounting principles by federal agencies, losses are not always being recorded or reported when they occur.'' From 1985 to 1988 losses on direct loans written off by the government increased 1,700 percent _ from $ 1.2 billion to $ 21.2 billion _ and delinquent loans rose by 33 percent, from $ 14.6 billion to $ 19.5 billion last year. But the loan guarantees adopted by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration as part of an effort to reduce direct government lending and the federal deficit pose even greater risks, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Many newer guarantee programs such as those for education and energy conservation involve loans with little or no marketable property as security,'' the auditors said. Others, such as those for small businesses which can not obtain credit in the private market otherwise, can quickly turn sour upon industry downturns and other changes in the economy, the auditors said. As one example, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> cited the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>'s student loan guarantee program, which has grown in size from $ 26.5 billion in 1983 to $ 47.6 billion last year During that same time, reported defaults on student loans have almost tripled, From $ 486 million in 1983 to more than $ 1.4 billion in 1988. In addition to the outstanding $ 222 billion in direct federal loans and $ 550 billion in loan guarantees, the government also is liable for $ 3.6 trillion in insurance commitments, most of it covering deposits in banks, S & amp; Ls and credit unions. Outstanding loans by government-sponsored enterprises, such as the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> Fannie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION>, total $ 656 billion, up from $ 15 billion in 1965. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., who requested the study as chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said it indicates that the government is `` guilty of the same shell game'' that critics of banks contend is being used to inflate beyond their true value their loans to Third World countries <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> did not question the value of the programs, saying many of served worthy purposes such as enabling people to attend college, buy homes and start businesses. `` What's at issue,'' he said, `` is the public's exposure in the event of losses or defaults.'' C
