<HEAD>SEC Chief Pushing Market Reform Legislation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A longer version is running on financial circuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> said Wednesday that he supports pending new market regulation legislation even though it does n't ban program trading. <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> told a group of reporters at <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> headquarters that the controversial, computer-driven trading strategy is only a symptom of bigger market problems. `` I think we need a close look at the whole issue of volatility and the factors that help produce it and the elements that may be at work. I'd like to make sure that before we treat only the symptom that we also are aware of what the disease is,'' he said. Critics of program trading, in which enormous blocks of stocks are bought or sold in a wink of an eye through computer-driven entry of buy and sell orders, say it can lead to excessive volatility _ sharp price rises and drops _ which in turn, scares small investors out of the market. And that, say the critics, makes it hard for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies to sell securities and raise capital. <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> said he supported recently amended legislation pending before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that would allow the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> to curtail trading practices found to be `` manipulative or abusive.'' `` I do n't think it gives us the authority to ban program trading per se,'' <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> said of the Securities Markets Stabilization Act of 1989. `` The thrust of this section is not to ban program trading as one practice in the marketplace. But what it does allow us to do is to specify specific harmful practices, including those associated with program trading.'' If the bill was passed, said <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> could then `` define rules that would bar specific practices that we deem to be harmful and contributing to excessive volatility and those practices could include program trading.'' Originally the bill would have allowed the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> to intervene when it considered trading practices to be `` disruptive,'' but members of the telecommunications and finance subcomitee argued that the word was too vague. In a letter to the subcommittee, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Glauber </PERSON>, an undersecretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> argued the word `` is itself disruptive.'' <PERSON> Glauber </PERSON> wrote that it could `` derail the chances for final passage of other important provisions included in this legislation.'' The bill must be passed by the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> before going to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. Congressional leaders have said they want to adjourn for the holidays next week. A similar bill is slated to be considered by the <ORGANIZATION> Seanate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Thursday.
