<HEAD>Migrant Workers Fall Ill From Pesticide Exposure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RUSKIN, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 100 migrant farmworkers were treated for vomiting, dizziness and heart and breathing problems Wednesday after they were exposed to a toxic pesticide in a cauliflower field, officials said. Morning workers at Goodson Farms began falling ill as soon as they entered a 16-acre field which had been sprayed the previous afternoon with the pesticide phosdrin, farm employees said. `` This is a pesticide we use all the time. As soon as it's dry, it's safe to go in there,'' said farm manager <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Almond </PERSON>. `` But this morning, one got sick and pretty soon they all started getting sick.'' Phosdrin is a common, though highly toxic, pesticide sprayed on a wide variety of agricultural crops to control worms. The label warns that fields sprayed with it should not be entered without protective clothing for at least 48 hours, said <PERSON> Tasha </PERSON> <PERSON> Brew </PERSON>, a pesticide education specialist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION>'s cooperative extension service `` Sometimes we go in about an hour after spraying, so long as it's dry,'' Almond said. `` This did n't stop us. We got people back out there now.'' The workers wore protective boots and gloves to protect them from any pesticide residue, he said. Crew managers at the farm began taking the first workers to a rural clinic, and later ambulances were dispatched to bring in more. `` The pesticide enters through the skin, so we first had to strip their clothes off, shower them and wrap them in sheets,'' said <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, administrator at the <ORGANIZATION> Ruskin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Migrant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. `` They were covered with it.'' Most of the workers suffered from vomiting, dizziness and blurred vision, with a handful showing breathing and heartbeat problems, said Ms. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, adding that a total of 77 had come through the clinic by late afternoon. Four patients were admitted to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in nearby <LOCATION> Sun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> with depressed heartbeats and breathing problems, said hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Oona </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>. About 25 others were treated and released at <ORGANIZATION> Tampa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, with the rest treated at the clinic, officials said. Almond said the workers were in the fields tying leaves around the cauliflower to keep the fleshy part of the plants from yellowing. The plants were scheduled to be harvested in about eight days.
