 </PERSON>'s connections to the hilt,'' referring to diplomatic friends he had in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. `` It seems to me to me a chance in a lifetime.'' Ms. <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> said her daughter referred to <PERSON> Mounir </PERSON> as her `` therapist and really good friend.'' Ms. <PERSON> Fahrend </PERSON>'s sister, <PERSON> Emily </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON>, 59, also of <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, said in an interview that her sister chose the name Fahrend, which means traveling or itinerant in German, as a pen name while living in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> several years ago. `` She tackles life pretty much head-on,'' Ms. <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON> said. `` She would be unaware of danger in thinking of going to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, instead thinking of the opportunities for professional advancement.'' She described the family's reaction as `` a state of shock.'' <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> McCullough </PERSON>, a friend of Ms. <PERSON> Fahrend </PERSON> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Geronimo </LOCATION>, a town 20 miles north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> where she is said to have lived until 1987, said they last met when her friend visited in June. She said the description `` publisher-journalist'' surprised her. She said Ms. <PERSON> Fahrend </PERSON>, who she indicated was divorced and had two daughters, was a registered nurse and sometime poet. `` She traveled extensively and was a poet _ wrote poetry about the places she visited,'' Ms. <PERSON> McCullough </PERSON> said. A <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the department had no information on Ms. <PERSON> Fahrend </PERSON> and `` we're trying to find out if she had a waiver on her passport.'' Americans are prohibited from traveling to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> without such a waiver of the rules. The documents showed one-entry visas issued for Ms. <PERSON> Fahrend </PERSON> and the two Germans by Consul <PERSON> Michelene </PERSON> <PERSON> Baz </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> Lebanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, on Nov. 1. Attempts to reach Ms. <PERSON> Baz </PERSON> on Wednesday night were unsuccessful. Other Lebanese diplomatic sources in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION> said further details about the visa applications would be available Thursday morning. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> said he had no information on the kidnappings. The American Embassy in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> has been closed since Sept. 22. The documents also showed entry stamps by the <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> security department at the Christian port of <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION> north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, dated Nov. 3, an indication the three traveled from <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> together by sea. No information was available on whether they remained in the Christian sector or crossed to Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> before their abduction. The West German Embassy in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> said it had no knowledge of the abduction until the statement was released after nightfall. If the kidnapping is confirmed, Ms. <PERSON> Fahrend </PERSON> would be the only Western woman now held captive in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, where women have been kidnapped only rarely. One was <PERSON> Danielle </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, daughter of French hostage <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Carton </PERSON>, who was kidnapped with her father in 1985 by <PERSON> Islamic </PERSON> <PERSON> Jihad </PERSON>, a Shiite Moslem group loyal to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, and released 12 hours later. Carton was held more than three years later. Ms. <PERSON> Fahrend </PERSON>'s father was identified in the visa photocopy as <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> and her mother as <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>. Her passport was issued in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> Oct. 15, 1984. Eighteen other foreigners are held in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, including eight Americans. Held longest is <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, 42, chief <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> correspondent of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, who was kidnapped March 16, 1985. Most of the hostages are believed held by pro-Iranian factions.
