<DATELINE>HILL AIR FORCE BASE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> security policeman pleaded guilty Wednesday to stealing more than $ 3,900 in military supplies from a base where two other security men pilfered F-16 jet engines. <ORGANIZATION> Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Base Staff Sgt. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eastabrook </PERSON> was to begin his court-martial Wednesday, but instead entered the plea as part of an apparent plea-bargain. <PERSON> Eastabrook </PERSON> was to have been the first man to face general court-martial as a result of `` Operation Punchout,'' a 2 -LCB- - year undercover investigation of military thefts from bases in the West and <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> Fourteen Hill personnel have been charged to date, with seven facing military courts-martial and seven indicted by a federal grand jury. Two other <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> security policemen have pleaded guilty to stealing three F-16 jet engines and selling them to undercover agents. They await sentencing in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The two charges against <PERSON> Eastabrook </PERSON>, 28, alleged that between October 1986 and April he stole almost 100 items and illegally sold them to Military Surplus Brokers, an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> front in <LOCATION> Roy </LOCATION>. In the plea-bargain, <PERSON> Eastabrook </PERSON> pleaded guilty to both charges, but to stealing slightly more than $ 3,900 rather than the $ 5,304 he originally had been charged with. The remaining goods were apparently items he had been issued, officials said. Lawyers on both sides said military justice rules prevented them from discussing the plea-bargain. Three other <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> enlisted men have gone through special courts-martial on charges they illegally sold military supplies. Two were acquitted and one was found guilty, demoted and sentenced to a month in jail. On Tuesday, another <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> security policeman pleaded guilty to three counts of theft of government property. Airman 1st Class <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Oltmanns </PERSON>, 21, from <LOCATION> Moose </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, is scheduled to stand trial Jan. 8. <PERSON> Oltmanns </PERSON> is charged with stealing aircraft aviation instruments, military gear and miscellaneous clothing items between July 1988 and February 1989.
