<HEAD>Ford's Executive Succession Plan Almost Unique</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The realignment of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION>'s executive suite, in which an older chief executive will replace a younger one and the four top positions will be held by men age 55 or older, is almost unique in recent history. It has upset patterns established over three decades, conceivably put another one in motion and presented a challenge to those who analyze and seek to understand the executive suite. `` It is the most unusual succession pattern of the 35 years in which I have audited executive mobility and succession in top corporations,'' said Professor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, an authority on such matters. Older executives have been favored over youth in the past, <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> said, but usually because directors lacked confidence that younger ones were ready, or because a company was rebuilding and sought to avoid radical change. He indicated this was not the situation at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and speculated that a feeling developing on corporate boards _ that many companies are losing experience and wisdom through early retirements _ may have played a role. In the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> realignment, chairman and chief executive <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON>, 63, will resign early in 1990 and be replaced by Vice Chairman <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Poling </PERSON>, 64. The chief executive's office also would include <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 60, as president and chief operating officer, <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilmour </PERSON>, 55, as head of worldwide automotive works, and <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Seneker </PERSON>, 58, as chief financial officer. <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor of management and a consultant to boards on succession policy, said that over the past three decades the typical age has been 55 years for new chairmen and 48 years for new presidents. In his view, <PERSON> Poling </PERSON>'s age presents him with a difficult situation in which he is denied the `` open-ended tenure'' that a new chief executive usually needs in which to make an imprint. That situation could become more complicated, <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> believes, because history shows that in the rare instances in which corporations preferred age over youth the seasoning of younger executives was impeded and frustrated. If <PERSON> Petersen </PERSON> has indeed ushered in a cultural revolution at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, says <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, `` then now is the time to use some of these senior positions to grow future top management.'' That `` is what conventional planning dictates.'' Noting that the chief executive's office now will be filled by four finance-oriented managers, <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON> observed it would be logical that a marketing or manufacturing executive be moved in among them to benefit from their knowledge. In the past when older financial people remained in top positions, said <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, it usually indicated the corporate directors felt the risk of change far outweighed the need for fresh ideas. He noted that <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, which earlier became the most profitable American automobile company, recently suffered declines in its quarterly profits and that it might indeed feel the future demands financial wisdom and experience. But <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, who pioneered in mobility studies during the 1950s, said the notion can not be ruled out that <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> might be in the vanguard of a new appreciation of age and competency.
</TEXT>
