<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Nov. 20, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Welfare Recipients Earn Cash To Attend Job-Training Classes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An accompanying story is BC-Cash-No Pregnancies, b0340.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATTY REINERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorpe </PERSON> wants a job. She wants a place to live in a drug-free neighborhood where she and her two toddlers will feel safe. And she wants to get off welfare. `` Ever since I've had these kids, I've had this fear _ that I'd always be financially dependent,'' said <PERSON> Thorpe </PERSON>, 28 `` These kids are depending on me, and I do n't want to let them down.'' Despite a failed marriage, the lack of a job and no day care for her 2 -LCB- - year-old daughter and 1-year-old son, she has a better chance to fulfill that goal now, thanks to an experimental job training effort that rewards determination with cash bonuses `` I would love to get into computers,'' <PERSON> Thorpe </PERSON> said. `` I'd like to try to be a word processor.'' Officials here in <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, frustrated by the lack of participation in job-training programs, started a three-year pilot program in July offering cash incentives of up to $ 1,000 to motivate welfare recipients to go to school and get jobs. `` It's no longer good enough to just give people a -LRB- welfare -RRB- check,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Caulk </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> for the county, which borders <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> `` We've got to do more to provide them with the wherewithal to get off of welfare, to break that cycle of dependence.'' The program, which targets those who have been receiving Aid to Families with Dependent Children for at least three years and low-income teen-age parents, is the first in the nation to offer cash incentives for job training, Caulk said. Participants who complete a goal, such as consistently attending a training class or earning a high school equivalency diploma, receive payments ranging from $ 25 to $ 200, with a limit of $ 1,000 per person per year. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Departments of <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> agreed to waive requirements that would have deducted the incentive payments from welfare or food stamp payments. The program will cost nearly $ 1 million in federal, state and county funds, Caulk said. But the annual savings in welfare benefits alone would be about $ 5,000 for each three-member family that becomes economically self-sufficient, he said. Social workers set up goals and payments, taking into consideration each person's abilities and motivation level. `` We're trying to empower case managers to have the flexibility to say, ` For this client, just showing up five days in a row is an accomplishment,''' he said. `` That person would be rewarded at the end of five days. Somebody else may have a totally different kind of package. They may have to score well in word processing or assembly or retail training. Others may get one payment to complete the class.'' About 600 people will participate in the experimental program, with half receiving cash incentives and the other half acting as a control group. `` The federal government suggested we keep payments quiet'' so the control group would n't know others were receiving payments for completing the same tasks they did without pay, <ORGANIZATION> Caulk </ORGANIZATION> said. `` But that is impossible because they're all in the same classes, and we want them to discuss their progress and encourage each other.'' Wealthy <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> has tried other projects in the past. Three years ago, it gave welfare recipients vouchers worth up to $ 250 to pay for food, utilities or other bills in exchange for their participation in job-training programs. The dropout rate was more than 50 percent. The federal government's approach to the problem is to require certain welfare recipients to attend job-training classes to keep their public assistance checks coming. But Caulk said even the threat of losing payments they now receive has not helped motivate some welfare recipients to seek advancement. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed the Family Support Act, requiring states to set up large-scale education, job-training and work programs to make welfare recipients self-sufficient. <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> was the first state to implement the act in all counties, said <PERSON> J.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shay </PERSON>, spokesman for the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>, who added that state officials are optimistic about <LOCATION> Montgomery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s program. `` We're anxious to see how the cash incentives will impact on the welfare recipients' participation, motivation and continuation in the program,'' he said. Federal officials are taking a wait-and-see attitude. `` We're not in favor of the program or against it, but if it is successful we'd like to see it tried in other areas,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Germanis </PERSON> of the federal Low-Income Opportunity Board, which includes officials from several federal agencies who are working to improve the nation's welfare system. `` And if it were to succeed in several areas, it could be used for reforming the national wefare system.'' Already, the program has surpassed Caulk's expectations. `` Our goal was to have 40 people in the first -LRB- job-training -RRB- class. So far, 61 people have enrolled,'' he said. `` Going on past experience, we could lose half in the next month.'' If the program works, however, the cash incentives would encourage them to stay, he said. `` This has never been tried before, so if we find that the payments make no difference, even that is worth knowing,'' Caulk said. `` Then we can sit down and think of something else to try.'' <PERSON> Thorpe </PERSON> said she is confident the program will work. `` When people ask me, ` What have you been up to?' I do n't say, ` Oh, nothin', just hangin' around.' I say: ` I've been busy. I'm going to school I'm going to get a job.''' And although she'd seek training even without being paid, she said, `` The money really comes in handy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, Nov. 20</NOTE>
