<HEAD>The Artists: The Passion of Georgia O'Keeffe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Passion and commitment to her art drove <PERSON> Georgia </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s painting, which both illuminates her appeal and adds a compassionate dimension to the O'Keeffe legend, according to a recent biographer. <PERSON> Roxana </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, author of `` <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> O'Keeffe: A Life,'' said the artist endures because she painted emotion in the 20th century. `` From the start of this century, painting in this country has been done in the masculine tradition, -LRB- which -RRB- has been either cold or angry. <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s paintings are passionate, tender and full of joy. And specifically they refer to the female experience,'' she said in a recent interview. The findings by <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, aided in her study by cooperation from <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s family, come in contrast to popular notions that <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON> was detached, even cool about her work and relationships. She draws from <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s letters and interviews with her associates and relatives to trace the artist's life from childhood on the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> prairie in the early 1900s through her tumultuous marriage to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> photographer and art impresario <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Stieglitz </PERSON>. `` <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> O'Keeffe: A Life'' -LRB- <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> and Row, $ 25 -RRB- also examines <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s complicated relationship with <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, a 23-year-old drifter who appeared on her doorstep looking for work in 1973 and stayed until her death. The letters discount the persistent sexual interpretations of <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s work. `` She was much warmer and more vulnerable than I expected,'' said <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, a novelist and art historian. `` She was also probably colder and more difficult, too. But doing the research I began to understand why.'' <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s life on the prairie as the eldest daughter of a farming family with six siblings taught her the importance of self-sufficiency; her independence was established early in life. `` I am going to live a different life from the rest of you girls,'' she said upon graduating from high school. `` I am going to give up everything for my art.'' Her love for <PERSON> Stieglitz </PERSON>, who was nearly two decades her senior, was strong, and he not only was enamored with her, but as a leading figure in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s art world he was also her greatest booster. `` If you were a woman and a painter, you were a woman painter. And that was very different from being a painter,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. `` It was important that she had somebody that was at least trying to get her work perceived as equal to men. But he did n't promote her work as any better than it actually was.'' <PERSON> Stieglitz </PERSON>, however, was also <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s greatest source of pain, but she never confronted him with his appetite for other young women. Again, her family ethic of self-sufficiency allowed her to cope. She demanded her solitude to work and began to spend about half the year apart from her husband, painting in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The O'Keeffe legend portrays her as a woman who just decided she was leaving one morning, but <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s pain was deep. `` At that period of her deepest grief and unhappiness she turned her energies toward her art instead of her anguish,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. `` If <PERSON> Stieglitz </PERSON> chose to make her unhappy, her job was to see that she was not unhappy. It was not to change his behavior.'' <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON> died in 1986 at the age of 98. The research alone makes <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>'s book worth reading, although her prose is sometimes redundant and her own pronouncements on feminism often blunt the message <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s life so clearly illustrated. The book does not raise the issue of <ORGANIZATION> O'Keeffe </ORGANIZATION>'s supposed bisexuality because, <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said, she could not produce any corroborating evidence. The sexual content of much of <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s bright and flowing flowers has long been debated, most vehemently by the artist herself. `` When you took time to really notice my flower, you hung all your own associations with flowers on my flower,'' <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON> wrote to one critic. `` And you write about my flower as if I think and see what you think and see of the flower _ and I do n't.'' For <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>, the flowers were demonstrations of passion, but not specifically representing genitalia or sexual objects, <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> says. `` O'Keeffe's flowers were images drawn from a female perspective, which made them both new and suspect,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> wrote. Similarly, <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>'s later stark depictions of cattle skulls and bones she found on the desert of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> were often misinterpreted to symbolize death. `` I have wanted to paint the desert and I have n't known how,'' she wrote in an exhibition catalog. `` So I brought home the bleached bones as my symbols of the desert. To me they are as beautiful as anything I know. ... The bones seem to cut sharply to the center of something that is keenly alive in the desert even tho' it is vast and empty and untouchable _ and knows no kindness with all its beauty.'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> portays <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON> as a leading example of the changing roles of women throughout the 20th century. `` <PERSON> Georgia </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Keeffe </PERSON>, by her example, gave permission to the following generations of women to give work priority in their lives, to consider it crucial,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> writes. `` Her paintings ... were about something that had never been before so clearly revealed: the female experience.''
