<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Burning Down the House With a New Latin Beat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Forsaking African rhythms, jazz arrangements and avant-garde electronics of previous Talking Heads and solo efforts, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>'s latest musical safari has brought him to the seductive beats of <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` It's a little different, maybe,'' <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> said from the stage of the Pantages theater to the bobbing concertgoers below. `` But maybe not,'' he quickly added, springing into another conga-laced tune. Those familiar with the hybrid tastes of <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, the lead singer of Talking Heads, knew just what he meant. Although his new album, `` <PERSON> Rei </PERSON> <PERSON> Momo </PERSON>,'' is infused with merengues and sambas, it's about as traditional a record as any he's made. `` I'm not trying to convert people, or educate people or do any of that kind of stuff,'' <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> said in an interview while stopping in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> during a national tour this fall. `` For me, it's purely something I'm getting a lot of enjoyment out of _ music that I think is deep and fun It's what I want to do. It's not as though I'm saying: ` Now, I want to tell you about this! You must sit down and listen!''' Unlike the contemplative, occasionally downcast themes cascading through <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>'s prior work, `` Rei Momo'' carries both invigorating lyrics and beats. In `` Do n't Want to Be Part of Your World,'' for example, he sings of children escaping an imperfect life to a place `` free from greed and hunger, free from hate and war.'' `` I think it is somewhat inherent in the culture _ the music, the melodies and rhythms _ that it can give you a kind of tinge of something uplifting, spiritual or whatever,'' the 37-year-old <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> said. `` In <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, there's a vast difference between the rich and the poor. The economy is in pretty bad shape. And yet they have these incredible cultural resources. The spirit of the people is very rich. `` Not only in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> but also in a lot of Latin culture, in the barrios in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> ... music is filled with the spirit of life. And you feel, ` This is what is allowing people to go on.' `` The music seems to reflect their lives and add something to their lives, rather than being the latest record that's foisted on them.'' <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> is the latest <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> artist to use Latin sounds in pop music in the 1980s. Others have included <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, who has worked with Brazilian star <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Nascimento </PERSON>, <PERSON> Quincy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> Transfer. <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON> recorded a song, `` La <LOCATION> Isla </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bonita </LOCATION>,'' which had a Latin flavor, and <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Ronstadt </PERSON> put out an album of Mexican favorites taught to her by her father. Twenty-five years after Brazilian music first caught American ears with the quiet strains of bossa nova, a second Brazilian invasion is occurring. Brazilian superstars such as <PERSON> Djavan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Simone </PERSON>, <PERSON> Caetano </PERSON> <PERSON> Veloso </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nascimento </PERSON> have been signed to American labels and are touring the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Latin music has likewise grown in popularity, with the arrival of crossover artists such as <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> Sound Machine and <PERSON> Reuben </PERSON> <PERSON> Blades </PERSON>. The co-founder of the 14-year-old but now idle Talking Heads, <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> has directed the film `` True Stories,'' acted in public television's `` Trying Times,'' and composed the scores for the <PERSON> Twyla </PERSON> <PERSON> Tharp </PERSON> dance `` The <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheel </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s opera `` The Forest'' and the movies `` The Last Emperor'' and `` Married to the Mob.'' For the 1986 movie `` Something Wild,'' he composed his first Afro-Latin single, `` Loco de Amor,'' sung by <PERSON> Celia </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON>, the queen of Latin music. It was scarcely a radical departure. In some of the 10 albums <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> has recorded with Talking Heads, especially 1980's `` Remain in Light'' and last year's `` Naked,'' his music has been laced with African sounds. <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> refined his appreciation for Afro-Latin compositions while spending six weeks in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> last year making a documentary about native dance-music rituals for public television's `` Alive From Off Center.'' In addition to `` <PERSON> Rei </PERSON> <PERSON> Momo </PERSON>,'' he has assembled two compilations of Brazilian hits, `` Beleza Tropical: <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> Classics, Volume 1,'' which reached the No. 1 position on Cashbox's Latin charts, and the new `` O Samba: <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> Classics, Volume 2.'' Because <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> enjoys a loyal following, his current tour is attracting mostly capacity audiences. `` Rei Momo'' debuted at No. 30 on the compact disc charts while the album was No. 109 after two weeks. Yet the people attending the concerts given by <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> and his 16-piece band are largely white Americans _ not the kind of audience usually seen at a concert where vocals are n't always in English and the bandstand is filled with such instruments as the coro and sencerro _ <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> drums _ and guiro, a percussion device. `` What we're doing will help the Latin scene ... a lot,'' said <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardona </PERSON>, a percussionist who appears on <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>'s album and tour. <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, who plays trumpet and arranged several of the album's songs, said: `` That's part of the excitement. To us, it's great to be bringing this music to a bigger audience And I think the public is ready for something new.'' Said <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>: `` You do n't have to understand it to enjoy it. `` I'm encouraged by the audience -LRB- but -RRB- I'm still afraid about radio,'' he said. `` When -LRB- radio stations -RRB- hear that it's a Latin record, they say, ` Whoa! We do n't play Latin music, we play the hits.''' For both the album and the 20-city tour that started in <LOCATION> Poughkeepsie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, in mid-September with plans for a South American and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> swing, <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> gathered some of the nation's leading Latin musicians _ veterans of bands for <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Blades </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> <PERSON> Puente </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> In assembling the record, <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> attempted to build songs that satisfied both his perfectionist personality and the music's latent disregard for formality. `` On the cumbia -LRB- ` Independence Day' -RRB-, for instance, I had a drum set up for the recording session,'' <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> said. `` And the drummer came in, and he hardly ever touched the drums. He usually would play the side of one of the tom toms. He did n't hit the snare drum once. So it was ... everything exactly the opposite of what a rock drummer would do. `` This was really different than recording with Talking Heads. For each song, we'd kind of cast the players in a way. ... If something was, say, a merengue, there are musicians who specialize in that kind of rhythm and those kind of bass parts, and we'd get those musicians in.'' While a few critics have accused the shy musician of international cultural vandalism, <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> says he's only creating new music out of old, as has been done for years. `` If everybody plays the same stuff, then nobody will listen to any of it,'' he said. `` I want to be free to do whatever I want to do. ... I get accused a little bit of flirting around with different styles, but I think a lot of them have an awful lot in common, and that I'm not jumping around as much as it may appear on the surface.''
