<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Nov. 24-26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: Caught in Time With Lucy and Ricky</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: National Book Award winners to be announced Nov. 29.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's been months since <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hijuelos </PERSON> has looked at his novel, `` The Mambo Kings Play Songs of Love,'' a nominee for the National Book Award. He remembers love scenes and music, but certain passages have slipped his mind; picking up the book again will be like reading it for the first time. It always works that way. Faces of old friends become blurred over the years. Listen to your favorite song 100 times and a note or turn of phrase will still surprise you. Only the most fanatical <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> fan can anticipate every joke. Memory, music, `` I Love Lucy'' _ they all matter in `` The Mambo Kings Plays Songs of Love'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Farrar </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Straus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Giroux </ORGANIZATION>, $ 18.95 -RRB-, in which <PERSON> Desi </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnaz </PERSON> briefly drops in on the world of brothers <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Nestor </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON>, and to their astonishment, transports them to the living room of <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ricky </PERSON> <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Arnaz </PERSON> was always one of the essential, successful Cubans,'' said <PERSON> Hijuelos </PERSON>, the son of <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> immigrants. `` He did n't have a down image. When you think about how Latins are portrayed in the media, even today, they're either hoods or they're cops. `` He was a middle-class man, very successful. He had a whacked-out life, but he had a real relationship, a real life, and that image really enchanted me. He also a slight melancholic streak. He had a lot of qualities that I related to.'' Try to remember this `` I Love Lucy'' episode: Two Cuban brothers, old friends of <PERSON> Ricky </PERSON>'s, arrive at the apartment one day. They exchange chitchat with the <ORGANIZATION> Ricardos </ORGANIZATION>, and later appear at the <LOCATION> Tropicana </LOCATION>, crooning `` Beautiful Maria of My Soul'' with the bandleader himself joining the brothers on stage. -LRB- <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON>, naturally, is upset because she wanted to appear in the show instead -RRB-. Sound familiar? Well, it never really happened, but that's the point. `` Mambo Kings'' is a song of invented memory, a mournful melody of events distorted by nostalgia and loss. `` The one thing you do n't lose is memory, and memory nags you,'' <PERSON> Hijuelos </PERSON> said. `` Look at Jewish writers who write about things that have happened, internally things go around and around and around. `` If you're hung up on the past you ca n't move forward. <PERSON> Nestor </PERSON> tries to get courage from the American notion of discarding the past and move forward.'' Loss of youth, love and country run through `` <ORGANIZATION> Mambo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kings </ORGANIZATION>.'' In the late 1940s, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> _ gregarious and ambitious _ and <LOCATION> Nestor </LOCATION> _ moody and romantic _ arrive in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> as aspiring mambo musicians. The end comes 30 years later, in a rundown hotel room where <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> drinks himself to death. Women inspire their songs and their songs inspire women. Love affairs for <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> are as intense, and short-lived, as the latest dance craze. For <PERSON> Nestor </PERSON>, heartbreak is timeless, a haunting ballad undiminished by repeated listenings. And memories of home are inescapable for both Castillos. No amount of rum, women and song can replace their simple, easygoing life in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. `` I think most immigrants are basically homesick,'' <PERSON> Hijuelos </PERSON> said. `` You ca n't imagine losing something like your country unless you've really lost it. It's just a dream of something lost, which you can never really retrieve. `` You meet Cubans in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> who have made a million bucks, but they will never have what they had before.'' <PERSON> Hijuelos </PERSON> was born in 1951 and grew up on 118th Street on <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Side </LOCATION>, a neighborhood remembered in his first novel, `` Our House in the Last World,'' published in 1985. He first wanted to be a musician, but was turned off by the rock' n' roll drug scene and drifted into writing in his mid-20s. <PERSON> Hijuelos </PERSON> nearly quit that as well, finding authors no more appealing than rock stars. `` I went to a writers conference in 1978 and I found it the most sexist, hierarchal, opinionated, prejudical place I've ever been on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. If you do n't write their way, you do n't write. If you're a woman and pretty, you get invited to parties, if not, forget it.'' Meeting author <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Barthelme </PERSON>, who died recently, provided <PERSON> Hijuelos </PERSON> with a valued friend and mentor. `` He sort of took me under his wing and pointed me in the right direction,'' <PERSON> Hijuelos </PERSON> recalled. `` He was n't narrow-minded in his view of literature and exposed me to a lot of writers. And even though I was writing quite differently from him, he never held that against me.'' `` He was a really nice man and a top-notch editorial adviser.'' <PERSON> Barthelme </PERSON> helped with `` Mambo Kings,'' and <PERSON> Arnaz </PERSON> and some not-so-famous musicians provided inspiration. <PERSON> Hijuelos </PERSON> recalled working in a downtown office where the elevator operator would come up to his floor and sing. A Cuban musician who died in a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> hotel room made a lasting impression. And, of course, there were songs, hundreds of them. `` Mambo Kings'' is like a greatest hits album, complete with <PERSON> Hijuelos </PERSON>' favorite dance songs, boleros and ballads <PERSON> Hijuelos </PERSON> urges readers to start where they wish, open at any page, like dropping the needle in the middle of a record, or tuning in `` I Love Lucy'' at intermission and quickly filling in the plot. `` <PERSON> Barthelme </PERSON> was like that. Instead of thinking of a chapter as a chapter, you think of it as an atmosphere, a state of consciousness,'' he said. `` I wrote this book where you can open it up anywhere and get an idea of what's going on in the book.''
</TEXT>
