<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Shirley Jones Records First Solo Album</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After a show business career of more than 30 years, including singing in movie classics such as `` Oklahoma!'' and `` The Music Man,'' <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> has released her first solo album. The Diadem Music LP `` Silent Strength'' is a collection of gospel songs. `` I grew up singing Christian music,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, 55, said in a telephone interview from her home in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` I was the youngest member of my church choir at age 6. `` It has been synonymous with my singing. It's beautiful music and this -LRB- project -RRB- was a wonderful experience. `` I've never really done a solo album. I've done the movie albums and did some things for <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> with my husband, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON>, and of course ` The Partridge Family.''' In 1970-74, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> was <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Partridge </PERSON> in the popular TV comedy about a family that became successful in show business. She portrayed a widowed suburban mother and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Cassidy </PERSON>, her real life stepson, was <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Partridge </PERSON>. `` I did 23 motion pictures and nobody knew me until ` The Partridge Family,''' she said. `` But that's TV. The power of TV is the strongest power we have now. You become a friend to people. You're really not larger than life, but part of their family. `` The show had a combination of things. It had music for the time. We were a family in show business, an everyday family. Plus we had good actors. <PERSON> David </PERSON> was a teen hero and little <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonaduce </PERSON> was a wonderful young comedian. The chemistry worked.'' Her movie credits, besides `` Oklahoma!'' and `` The Music Man,'' include `` Carousel,'' `` Elmer Gantry'' -LRB- Academy Award for supporting actress in 1961 -RRB-, `` April Love'' and `` Beyond the Poseidon Adventure.'' Her most recent film was `` Tank'' with <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> three years ago. The Oscar, she said, changed her career. `` I was considered a pretty young thing who could sing until then. After that, they said that maybe this kid can act. It opened doors for me, no doubt.'' She also has appeared in several TV movies, including `` The Family Nobody Wanted,'' `` Winner Take All,'' `` The Orchard Children,'' `` Last Cry for Help'' and `` Silent Night, Lonely Night.'' Most dealt with topical issues such as gambling addiction, unjust adoption procedures and teen suicide. `` Those kind of roles are wonderful to play,'' Miss <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. She recently taped a two-hour tribute show to composer <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodgers </PERSON>, to be broadcast on the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> next March. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> also sings frequently with symphony orchestras across the country. One of her traditional songs is `` You'll Never Walk Alone'' from `` Carousel.'' The song is also on her solo album. `` It conveys a message to audiences of all types, whether Christian or Jewish or whatever,'' she said. `` Those words touch people. I've been singing it even before ` Carousel.' It's been part of my repertoire for 30 years now. When I think of the words during a distressing time, it helps me through.'' Among other cuts on the album, `` The Music's Got ta Stop Someday'' describes the emptiness of entertainment without content. The title cut `` Silent Strength'' is about trusting one's savior. `` We spent five hours in my living room one Sunday afternoon going through the music,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. `` We pored through music and talked about words and what was right for me. I wanted to do beautiful ballads with beautiful lyrics and no rock' n' roll stuff.'' She said she's at a point in her career where she accepts only projects that intrigue her. `` I'm at a marvelous place in my life. I'm not driven by my career, but I never have been really. I can pick and choose. I'm able to do what I want to do which is sing, basically.''
</TEXT>
