<HEAD>Grand Marnier Liqueur Plans Motorized Magazine Ad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The importers of Absolut vodka were nosed out recently by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in getting the first `` talking'' magazine ad to market. But <ORGANIZATION> Carillon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Importers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> is back, claiming a first for another of its brands _ a `` motorized'' magazine ad for Grand Marnier liqueur. When the center spread of the four-page ad is opened, a cardboard cutout that shows two fanciful birds with oranges on their bodies gently swinging a bottle of Grand Marnier between them as if it were a bell. The cutout is powered by a tiny battery embedded out of sight beneath the cutout. The <LOCATION> Teaneck </LOCATION>, N.J.-based importer said Tuesday it had spent more than $ 1 million on the four-page holiday ad that is to appear in selected copies of the Dec. 11 issue of the New Yorker. The ad will be included in the 200,000 issues of the magazine that are sent to subscribers in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state. The ad is the latest example of the extra effort some liquor advertisiers take to make their ads stand out at Christmastime. Absolut vodka's talking ad in selected copies of the December issue of Vanity Fair magazine delivered tinny holiday greetings in Italian, English and Spanish. But <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> ran an ad with a talking computer chip about two weeks earlier in Business Week magazine. Other holiday magazine ad spectaculars this year include a hologram from Finlandia vodka, an ad with pull-up tabs from Chivas Regal Scotch whisky and peel-off stickers from Crown Royal Canadian whisky. Some advertising executives have criticized the ad spectaculars, saying it detracts from the environment for their clients' ads. But others argue the unusual ads attract attention to a magazine and make consumers more aware of other magazines. `` Most people love to see this sort of thing in their magazines,'' said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Florio </PERSON>, president and chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yorker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` We thought this was innovative and creative and our readers would enjoy seeing it.''
