<HEAD>Hamburger Chain Founded By High School Dropout Celebrates 20 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CO3</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to correct LaserPhoto number.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER C. KENT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> celebrates its 20th anniversary today, its founder pledges to renew a dedication to customers that he believes the fast-food chain lost somewhere along the way. `` We forgot who the customer was,'' founder and former Chairman <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said in an interview this week. `` But in 1989, we're working hard on customer satisfaction and clean restaurants. The high school dropout opened the first <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s in downtown <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> on Nov. 15, 1969, naming it after his daughter. He stuck to a limited menu of hamburgers and chili that he believed was the only way to maintain quality. Today, the chain has grown to the nation's third - or fourth-largest, depending upon the criteria used, behind No 1 McDonald's and No. 2 Burger King, and possibly behind <PERSON> Hardee </PERSON>'s. It rakes in $ 3 billion in annual sales with a menu that has mushroomed to include pizza, salad, pasta, two types of chicken sandwiches, burritos, baked potatoes and chocolate chip cookies. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, who owns 8 percent, or $ 40 million, of <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s stock, said in a 1978 interview that he wanted <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s to be bigger than <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. Asked about that on Monday, he said: `` We still just want to be the best, the cleanest restaurant, the best prices, the best food. We'll be as big as we want to be.'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, who retired as chairman in 1982, now stars in his own folksy television ads for <ORGANIZATION> Wendy </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, which is based in nearby <LOCATION> Dublin </LOCATION>. Industry analysts say <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s started on the fast track and grew quickly, establishing 1,000 stores in nine years and becoming the No. 3 fast-food chain before its recent slide. `` They developed a unique niche targeting the adult fast-food segment of the hamburger industry with a tightly-focused menu,'' said analyst <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>. `` But <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s seems to have lost some of its focus as it tried to expand its menu and diversify into breakfast, which was not successful, and spent a lot of money upgrading its restaurants,'' he said. `` They've seen their market share erode along the way.'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said the diversification was necessary. `` In 1979, we had a real problem with beef, and the price went way up, and the word ` nutrition' started appearing, so we put in the salad bar. Competition was getting keener, so we added a lot of things. I do n't think we could have the same menu as we did in'69 and be successful,'' he said. Average sales at <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s 3,762 restaurants rose 2.4 percent to $ 759,000 per store last year, breaking a three-year decline. <ORGANIZATION> Hardee </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> reported average sales of $ 920,000 at its 3,200 stores last year. Per-unit sales at <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s were highest in 1984, at $ 871,000. That was the year of <PERSON> Clara </PERSON> <PERSON> Peller </PERSON>'s commanding performance in the `` Where's the Beef?'' commercials. `` Advertising is an important part of the business, but it's not a cure-all,'' said analyst <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It may raise levels of awareness and bring customers in. But unless you're giving a hot hamburger to a customer in a clean place and quickly, all the advertising in the world is n't going to amount to a hill of beans,'' he said. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> pegged <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s share of the fast-food market at about 4.8 percent, trailing 5.5 percent for <ORGANIZATION> Hardee </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> has about 18.9 percent, <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said. To help boost sales, <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s last November started installing a system allowing customers to pay for food with a Visa card. Tests show people spend more when they use credit cards, the company said. Earnings for the third quarter totaled $ 8.7 million, or 9 cents a share, on revenue of $ 296.2 million, compared with the same profit on revenue of $ 275.2 million for the same period last year. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said that, for now, the company will continue a strategy of making existing stores more profitable and opening new units at a slower pace _ about 100 a year. `` We've got to take business from competition, business from anyone,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> said. `` We've got to take care of the customers, just like we did 20 years ago.''
