<HEAD>Car and Truck Sales Continue Slump</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The sales slump in domestically made cars and light trucks continued in early November, prompting speculation that automakers will bring back incentives to attract buyers. `` The hard thing to read is which of the Big Three is going to move quickly next to reinvigorate sales with new incentive programs,'' analyst <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillippi </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday after sales figures were released. The eight major automakers with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plants said they sold cars and light trucks at an average daily rate of 26,194 during the Nov. 1-10 period compared with a 32,833-a-day pace during the same time last year. Car sales dropped 23.1 percent, while sales of light trucks fell 15.3 percent during the period, compared with early November last year. In October, domestic car and truck sales tumbled 11.6 percent from the rate of October 1988. The drop in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> car and truck sales last month pushed down October retail sales by 1 percent, the first decline in eight months. `` We are in the midst of an automotive recession,'' said analyst <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Merlis </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` For anybody in this economy, these types of numbers today are not funny. `` It's scary,'' he said. `` I do n't think they are going to continue. I hope they wo n't continue.'' One of the ways automakers have accelerated auto sales recently is through cash rebates or cut-rate financing. The companies had incentive programs on a wide variety of 1989 models but have less extensive programs now. <PERSON> Merlis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Phillippi </PERSON> said that could change. `` Any one of them -LRB- the Big Three -RRB- has a good reason to increase them,'' <PERSON> Phillippi </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Merlis </PERSON> said he expected bigger incentive packages to be combined with production cuts, a move analysts have been expecting for months. `` You need more than just incentives to get inventories in line,'' he said. `` This is an old-fashioned cyclical downturn with a very sad effect on the general economy.'' Sluggish car and light-truck sales during October and early November have pushed the year-to-date sales rate down 2.6 percent compared with the same time last year. Car sales are down 3.6 percent and truck sales are off 0.8 percent. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said its early November combined domestic car and truck sales were down 26.3 percent compared with last year, with car sales dropping 29.1 percent and truck sales falling 20.9 percent. Sales of vehicles made in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> were off 19.9 percent in early November, as car sales fell 23.5 percent and truck sales dropped 14.3 percent. At <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, car sales during the period were down 22.5 percent and truck sales were down 9.9 percent, combining for a 16.6 percent drop in the early November vehicle sales pace.
