<FIRST>r f PM-MarketReforms     11-15 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Market Reforms,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Market Reform Bill Clears First Hurdle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bill giving the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> limited authority to control program trading in market emergencies has cleared its first hurdle. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> telecommunications and finance subcommittee, after a sometimes heated debate over whether it was too much too soon, voted Tuesday to send the bill to the full <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> for consideration, possibly as soon as Thursday. Congressional leaders have said they want to end the current session before Thanksgiving. `` I'm not convinced it's something we should have such a rush to judgment,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>. `` We all know we're not going to get this through <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and down to the White House before the end of the year anyway,'' he added. But Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>, D-Ore., said `` I think it would be unconscionable to leave this congressional session without sending a message to the markets. The bill, known as the Securities Markets Stabilization Act of 1989, would give the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> new authority to suspend or constrain practices that could cause market volatility _ sharp price rises and drops. Chief among those controversial practices is program trading, the almost instantaneous, computer-driven transactions involving huge blocks of stock. The proposed legislation also: _ Would give the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> authority, after consulting with the president, to halt all trading in the securities markets in the event of an emergency like the 1987 stock market crash _ Require large securities transactions to be reported _ Require the parent and affiliated companies of securities and investment firms to verify their financial stability with the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> Another provision that calls for coordinated clearing and settlement of transactions among the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> and other government agencies was moved into a separate bill, the Coordinated Clearance and Settlement Act, which also passed the subcommittee. A similar bill is pending in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> but <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leaders have expressed doubts that they can add a program trading provision and still get it passed before the holiday break. The provision giving the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> modified authority to halt program trading was approved only after the panel agreed to an amendment by Rep. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Rinaldo </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, the subcommittee's ranking Republican, limiting the description of practices the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> could halt or prohibit. `` This language does not ban program trading and it does not direct the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> to ban program trading,'' said <PERSON> Rinaldo </PERSON>. `` It allows the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> to use its discretion in limiting or curtailing disruptive trading strategies.'' Opponents of program trading are particularly critical of one form, index arbitrage, in which speculators try to take advantage of inconsistencies between the stock and futures markets by simultaneously buying in one while selling in the other. Critics claim index arbitrage leads to wild price swings which drives small investors out of the market. And that makes it harder for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies to raise capital through the sale of securities, they claim. Originally, the bill sought to prohibit `` manipulative, abusive or disruptive practices'' but several panel members complained that language was too vague. When Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., the subcommittee chairman, offered his assurance that he would hammer out suitable compromise language before the bill went to the full committee, Rep. W.J <PERSON> Tauzin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., said, `` What I do n't think what we ought to do is move on language we ca n't agree upon. Other members complained that they needed more time to review the most recent changes in the bill, some of which were added just the night before. `` In the waning days of the session,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Manton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, `` I think we're moving rather fast.'' That sparked an outburst from <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>: `` We have had hearing after hearing after hearing,'' he said, noting that several big Wall Street securities firms that oppose program trading were repeatedly invited to testify at those hearings but `` they turned us down every time.'' <PERSON> Rinaldo </PERSON>'s amendment deleted the word `` disruptive'' from the bill, which seemed to satisfy opponents pending further negotiations on appropriate language.
