<HEAD>Senate Extends Tax Breaks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Senate has voted to extend through June 30 a dozen targeted tax breaks that are expiring, including employer-financed education assistance. The extensions, most of them for six months, were approved by voice vote Tuesday without debate and added to a bill authorizing aid to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. That measure is subject to further consideration by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. Each of the extensions had been approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> as part of other legislation. Among the extended provisions are those offering tax reductions for up to $ 5,250 per year of employer-paid education aid received by a worker; a limited amount of employer-financed group legal aid; businesses that increase spending for research and experimentation; investment in rental housing for low-income families; self-employed people to help cover the cost of health insurance; employers who hire low-income people, and investors in bonds targeted to help lower-income families buy a first home. Most of the tax breaks are due to expire Dec. 31. The deduction for employer-financed education assistance expired last Dec. 31. The amendment adding the provisions to the Poland-Hungary bill was written by Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo. `` If we allow them to expire, real damage can be caused,'' <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> said. He cited, for example, the low-income housing credit as about the only federal aid now available for that sector. `` If we decide it is just going to go away for however long it takes until we can re-enact it, there can be some real damage to low-income housing,'' he said. The cost of the extensions, an estimated $ 1.2 billion, would be made up by accelerating the rate at which large corporations must turn over to the government the taxes they withhold from workers' paychecks
