<SECOND>BC-Japan-Superconductivity,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>``Sustained Effort'' Seen in Slog Toward Superconductivity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TSUKUBA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leading researchers into superconductivity said Wednesday some progress was coming faster than expected but many problems remain in a scientific field that may revolutionize the use of electricity. About 700 scientists, including some 70 from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and elsewhere outside <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, are in <LOCATION> Tsukuba </LOCATION>, a university town outside <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, for three days of lectures, papers and discussions on the latest research into superconductivity, which has obsessed thousands of scientists since a breakthrough in 1986. `` I think the development goes faster than I thought,'' said <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>, who won the Nobel Prize for the 1986 breakthrough at <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> laboratories in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. Superconductors are materials that carry electricity without any loss of energy from resistance. The phenomenon was first seen at extremely low temperatures, but since 1986 scientists have developed a series of materials that work at somewhat higher temperatures, raising the possibility that the phenomenon will occur at temperatures that do n't require baths of liquid nitrogen. Superconductivity could make the use of electricity much more efficient, reducing the need to burn so much fossil fuel and opening the way for magnetically levitated high-speed trains, electric cars, better batteries, small supercomputers and many other uses. Competition among scientists is intense, and cries of alarm have been raised in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is investing more heavily in research and thus may make key commercial breakthroughs. `` There are many of the same parallel activities going on in the two countries,'' <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sleight </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, a featured speaker in the symposium's first session, told a news conference. `` The effort is somewhat better organized in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, but there is progress in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` People have many of the same objectives and are ... working toward those objectives.'' <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> said the European attitude is to remember that it took 20 years to develop a practical transistor. `` The important thing is to have sustained effort,'' he said.
