. Even with insurance covering the bulk of the libel award, the newspaper will suffer economically, <PERSON> Block </PERSON> said. A hiring freeze and other cost-saving measures implemented in response to the award will remain in effect until at least the end of the year, Business Manager <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> said. `` We will look at 1990 as a year when we get back to full staffing,'' <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Post-Gazette </ORGANIZATION> said the judgment was the largest paid by a newspaper and the second-largest libel judgment upheld by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts. The largest was a $ 3 million award last year against <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused to review the DiSalle libel award last June. National Surety attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Luddy </PERSON> said the settlement was not an admission that the company's position on punitive damages was incorrect. `` Some of these cases are better settled than litigated. This happened to be one of them,'' he said. `` Our position has n't changed.
