<SECOND>PM-CBOE Investigation,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exchange Probes Possible Manipulation of Stock-Options Exchange</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Options </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> is investigating the possibility that stock-index options were manipulated as part of program-trading activity, a published report says. The exchange is looking at trading in <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 100 stock index options during the Oct. 13 stock market plunge as well as other volatile trading days, the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> reported in today's editions. The <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION> is the fourth exchange to search for program-trading abuses. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and two other <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> exchanges are conducting a separate probe of computer-assisted program trading in stocks and stock-index futures. <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> told the Journal that the exchange is looking at `` sources of volatility,'' including trades, programs or otherwise, that may have involved manipulation or other forms of rule-breaking. `` We are looking at all volatile days,'' <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> said. `` We have been in touch with the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> frequently about the events, and they are well aware of the review that is being conducted.'' Exchange officials did not immediately return telephone calls seeking comment. For years, the <ORGANIZATION> CBOE </ORGANIZATION> has been a source of rumors and suspicions about program-trading abuses, the Journal said. Those suspicions partially result from the complexity of options-related program-trading strategies that are only understood by the most sophisticated traders. Additionally, traders say program trades in S & amp; P 100 stock index options have moved the market in the past, the newspaper said. Program trading is the rapid buying and selling of stocks by computer to take advantage of temporary price differences. A stock option is the right to buy or sell the underlying value of a stock index, such as the S & amp; P 100, at a specified price within a specified time. The unique feature of stock-index options is that they are settled by payment in cash, not with delivery or receipt or stocks. Also, S & amp; P 100 options can be exercised at any time before their expiration date. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> reported that the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P 100 options market re-emerged as a popular program-trading vehicle after the 1987 crash. A June 30 <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> memo said `` <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P 100 stock index options were often the second-most heavily used derivative product for index arbitrage from November 1988 to April 1989.'' Program trades involving the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P 100 options accounted for 8 percent to 19 percent of total index arbitrage volume for the six-month period, the commission said.
</TEXT>
