<FIRST>a f PM-OntheMoney Adv16   11-15 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 16,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Thurs Nov 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>Year-End Trap in Mutual Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As the end of the year approaches, financial advisers are issuing warnings about a trap that can spring on anybody who buys shares of mutual funds. If you are thinking about getting into a fund or making a substantial addition to an existing fund holding before year-end, they say, you should do a little extra research. The subject of that inquiry: Is the fund about to declare its annual distributions of dividends and capital gains? If the answer is yes, the experts say, you might seriously consider waiting to invest your money until after the record, or ex-dividend, date for those distributions, and thus miss sticking yourself with an unnecessary tax obligation. The trap works this way: To qualify for status as investment companies that do n't themselves have to pay taxes, most mutual funds must pass through substantially all of their investment income to their shareholders each year These distributions then become taxable, as dividends or capital gains, to the shareholders. The typical money-market fund or income fund investing in bonds declares its dividends daily, or at least monthly. So it does n't matter much what time of year you choose to invest in these By contrast, many stock funds or others that might earn capital gains _ for example, a fund investing in high-yield `` junk'' bonds that can fluctuate a great deal in price _ make all or a big chunk of their distributions once a year. The effective date of the distribution is often set between mid-December and the end of the year, for payment a few weeks later. If you buy fund shares just before the record date, you put yourself in the position of having some of your capital returned almost immediately to you, burdened with a tax liability, before it has had a chance to earn you any real return. `` You have acquired a share of the other stockholders' profits,'' says <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> in his Handbook For No-Load Fund Investors Suppose, for illustration purposes, that a fund's net asset value stands at $ 20 a share when you buy it just before the ex-distribution date. Then a $ 2 distribution is declared, lowering the net asset value to $ 18. Presumably, you do n't want this `` income'' in cash _ you just put the money into the fund. But even if you have it automatically reinvested in new shares, you ca n't duck the tax liability. No such problem arises if you wait until after the record date. Whatever amount you had set aside to invest will buy proportionately more shares at $ 18 than it would have at $ 20. Stock funds' distributions tend to be especially sizable in bull market years, such as 1989. Information about a fund's plans should be readily available through a simple phone call to the fund before you decide to buy. Of course, if the investment is being made in an individual retirement account or other program that shelters it from current taxes, the timing of distributions does n't matter. But among taxable investors, those who show up at the wrong time are presented with a share of the bill for a party they did n't attend
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs Nov 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
