<HEAD>Rhetoric Takes Center Stage in Takeover Battle Between Papermakers</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf pvs `The battle ...' to update with Georgia-Pacific
announcing financing commitments; picks up 5th graf pvs, `Also Tuesday
...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The rhetoric is heating up as <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> pursues its spurned bid to buy <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nekoosa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 3.1 billion, though both forest-products companies deny any nasty intent. Great Northern earlier this week rejected the <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> offer in a pair of sharply worded letters, one to its shareholders and the other to <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman. <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> responded with a statement to the media that bluntly questioned the motives of Great Northern's management in turning down the $ 58-a-share offer. <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> announced today that it has lined up commitments for $ 4.5 billion from 19 domestic and international banks to fund the takeover. The company said <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, its primary bank since the 1950s, has agreed to provide $ 1.25 billion of the amount. Also Tuesday, Great Northern announced it was challenging a ruling by the <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that cleared <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> to include <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION>'s four railroads in the proposed acquisition. <LOCATION> Norwalk </LOCATION>, Conn.-based Great Northern said the <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION> approved the clearance in one day when the process usually takes months. <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> `` cut corners'' and engaged in `` questionable tactics'' to get the ruling, <ORGANIZATION> Great </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> said. But Great Northern Chairman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Laidig </PERSON> told The <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> Journal-Constitution that he did not mean for his letter to <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> to seem sarcastic or harsh. And <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> said in an interview at his company's <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> headquarters Tuesday that he saw straightforwardness, not anger, in Great Northern's statements. <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> also said he did not expect <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION>, which he once described as `` a company of nice people,'' to get nasty as it tangles over the offer. `` I would hope not,'' he said. `` If you come and offer me 50 percent or more -LRB- profit -RRB- for more of my assets, I would think you're an awfully friendly guy. And I would probably embrace you for doing that. `` So I do n't see how offering a company 50 percent or more premium for what its assets have been selling for for the past two years would be considered unfriendly,'' he said. <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> plans to continue its pursuit of Great Northern, but declined to discuss strategy. <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> said all aspects of the proposal are negotiable, though he said the offer as it stands provides excellent short-term benefits for Great Northern shareholders and good long-term prospects for his company. <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> also dismissed concerns raised by Great Northern about antitrust implications of the proposed deal. He said he was not worried, either, about an anti-takeover regulations in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, where Great Northern is incorporated, that some say could block the deal. <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> said various conditions _ <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION>'s confidence in the strength of the industry, the company's ability to handle the debt from a takeover and the compatibility of the two companies _ made the time right to launch the bid. A takeover of Great Northern would be one of the largest acquisitions ever for <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION>, a company that has often used buyouts to grow over 62 years. <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> started in 1927 as a lumberyard in <LOCATION> Augusta </LOCATION>, when founder <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheatham </PERSON> made a $ 12,000 investment to start a hardwood wholesale business known originally as the <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hardwood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lumber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The company soon began to manufacture hardwood lumber, too. During World War II, it was the largest supplier of lumber to the military. After the war, in 1947, the company made its first <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> acquisition, a plywood plant in <LOCATION> Bellingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>. A string of acquisitions followed over the next 10 years It was during the 1950s, too, that the company changed its name to <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> and moved its headquarters to <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, where it remained until coming to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> in 1982. The company's roster of acquisitions continued to grow in the'60s and'70s; purchases from coast to coast included paper mills, a gypsum company, chemical plants, a kraft pulp mill, timberlands, sawmills and an oil company. Last year, the company spent $ 841 million on acquisitions. <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> also decided about 1983 to focus more narrowly on its pulp-and-paper and building products businesses. That resulted in the divestiture of some of its underperforming assets, notably the commodity chemicals business, which became <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Great Northern, as <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> sees it, fits right in with the company's growth pattern It explains why <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> is not worried about a `` white knight'' riding in to win <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> in a bidding war, <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> said. `` We believe that through the strategic combinations of the two businesses ... Great Northern is more valuable to <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> than it is to any other company,'' <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> said. Great Northern had 1988 sales of $ 3.6 billion. The company owns 3.5 million acres of timberland and has 20,000 employees at mills and factories in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Georgia-Pacific </ORGANIZATION> had $ 9.5 billion in sales last year, making paper, other forest products and building materials. It owns 6.5 million acres of timberland and 380 plants and mills employing 44,000 workers.
