<FILEID>AP-NR-11-15-89 1358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-OffshoreOilPort Adv19   11-15 0946</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Offshore Oil Port, Adv 19,0978</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Nov. 19 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Only U.S. Superport: It's Clean, But Will It Ever Make A Profit?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's only offshore port for supertankers has n't had a serious spill in eight years of operation, but it has n't had a profit, either. The clean but poor <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Offshore </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oil </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> is touted as a savior of the environment by some and a financial failure by others, leaving uncertain whether it will be a model for other ports around the country. Known as LOOP, the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Offshore </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oil </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> sits 19 miles off the coast in 115 feet of water _ deep enough for the biggest tankers in the world to tie up and unload their crude cargo. When it was proposed in 1972, supporters said it would cost $ 250 million, create tens of thousands of jobs and stimulate onshore investments. Environmentalists fought the idea, warning that it was had the potential for oil spills that could devastate <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s fragile wetlands. Both sets of predictions were confounded. LOOP cost more than $ 700 million and has yet to make a profit. However, it has been so clean that <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> thinks building more deep-water ports around the country would help avoid spills like one in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. `` The loss of oil has been just a thimble-full from every barrel that's been through there,'' he said after a visit to the port in September. `` And it confirms my original thought that the way to avoid oil spills is to make sure that tankers do n't run aground. That's what's happened in all our oil spills. LOOP looks like a three-deck offshore oil platform. Around it, 1 -LCB- miles away, are three buoys like floating, 42-foot-tall bird cages. Tankers tie up to those buoys while they pump oil through long hoses attached to concrete bases on the ocean floor. The five owners, in order of the size of their stakes, are <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Marathon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Murphy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The consortium is responsible for paying off the bonds for the project, which were issued by a state agency to qualify for tax-exempt status. Former Gov. <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> told reporters in 1974, shortly before taking office: `` The projections are that it could pay for itself in less than 10 years.'' Instead LOOP, after eight years of operation, still owes $ 565 million on $ 731 million in bonds, said controller <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simoneaux </PERSON>. It is handling about half the projected 63 million gallons of crude oil a day. It lost money until last year, when it broke even for the first time. Will it make a profit this year? `` I'd rather not comment on that,'' said R.C. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, president of LOOP, <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a consortium of five oil companies which own and operate the platform. LOOP depends on strong demand for imported oil, and backers were stunned when Americans responded to the 1970s jump in oil prices by conserving. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports of oil rose far less than expected in the 1970s and actually fell into the mid-1980s. LOOP's prospects have improved now that oil imports are rising again. Nationally, imports averaged about 8 million barrels a day for the first 10 months of 1989. LOOP is geared to oil hauled from the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> in supertankers _ behemoths which can not get into most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ports. `` Ironically, for LOOP to be successful, you have to import foreign oil,'' <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> said earlier this year. Oil imports are up around the country. `` That makes me believe that oil ports would be successful in other places,'' <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> said. LOOP has been almost squeaky clean. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> estimates that, out of 1.5 billion barrels of oil brought ashore since 1981, 850 have spilled. That works out to about a teaspoonful for every 2,300 gallons moved. Three gallons spilled in all of 1987. LOOP's location eliminates the threat of groundings and lessens the chance that a spill could come ashore. Radar keeps a continuous sweep over a 36-square-mile safety zone and special mooring masters guide the big ships to and from LOOP's buoys. `` <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> said it's going to cost them $ 1.5 billion to clean up Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> and the surrounding area. ... Would n't it be better to spend $ 1.5 billion to prevent oil spills than to spend it cleaning it up?'' <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> said. Environmentalists are n't convinced that superports are the answer. Alternatives could include building tankers with double hulls, improving traffic control and reactivating <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> stations, said <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Speer </PERSON>, senior scientist at the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In addition, said <PERSON> Speer </PERSON>, construction and maintenance of such ports also could hurt the environment, and beaches can be affected by spills 20 miles away. `` In <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, within a few hours you had a spill that had covered 25 square miles,'' she said. `` Offshore spills can still impact the shore.'' And $ 1.5 billion is a drop in the barrel of possible costs for a system of offshore ports such as <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> envisions, with deep-water ports off of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. To replicate LOOP would cost more than $ 800 million and probably more than $ 1 billion, by various estimates. <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Connaughton </PERSON>, marine transportation associate with the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said he's seen estimates as high as $ 2 billion. On top of that, oil users such as refineries that now get direct deliveries would have to hook up to a network of as-yet-unbuilt pipelines. Building those could be even more expensive than building the ports, <PERSON> Connaughton </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
