<HEAD>British Airways' Profit Up 16.5 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday reported that its net profit jumped 16.5 percent in the second quarter of its fiscal year, boosted by strong passenger traffic. The airline, one of the world's largest, said its net profit in the three months ended Sept. 30 rose to 106 million British pounds, or around $ 172 million, from 91 million pounds, or $ 147.4 million, a year earlier. Per-share earnings increased 16.7 percent to 14.7 pence, or 23.8 cents, from 12.6 pence, or 20.4 cents. `` Our profits for the second quarter are the highest yet reported for those three months by any airline in the world,'' Lord King, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>' chairman, said in a statement. The airline reported increased passenger traffic for the period, including a one-month record in September of 2.2 million passengers carried. Much of the growth came on flights between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the company said. Second-quarter revenue rose 13.4 percent to 1.4 billion pounds, or $ 2.2 billion, from 1.2 billion pounds, or $ 1.9 billion. Last month, <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> withdrew from a group led by pilots and top managers seeking to buy <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 6.75 billion, after the group failed to obtain adequate financing for the deal. The British airline had planned to invest $ 750 million in Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>, the parent of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, in return for a 15 percent stake in the company. King said in the statement <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> was `` disappointed'' that its proposed investment in <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZ