<FIRST>u f PM-CapitalGains 2ndLd-Writethru f0113 11-15 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Capital Gains, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0113,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Buries Capital-Gains Cut for the Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with vote; picks up at pvs 9th graf, Bush promised
... Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> today refused for the second day in the row to shut off debate on President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposed capital-gains tax cut, killing the issue for the year. The vote was 51-47, nine short of the 60 required to limit debate. The margin was the same on Tuesday. `` In the end, we will win this battle'' next year, Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, R-Ore., said after the first vote <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> leaders had agreed in advance that the two days of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> debate on the proposal would put the issue to rest until next year. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> earlier today, presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> told reporters, `` We consider yesterday's vote just the beginning.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> promised a capital gains cut in last year's presidential campaign as a way to encourage investment and create jobs. The proposal has dominated debate over budget issues for several months. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, pleaded for Democratic loyalty and assailed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for spending so much effort to win the cut. A reduction, <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said, would bloat the deficit by tens of billions of dollars in the long run and serve up a major tax windfall for the nation's richest people. `` This amendment evinces no concern about investment or with the future,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. `` It is concerned only with the present and the political benefits that may flow from cutting taxes ... `` Given our circumstances, when so many in our nation are without decent housing, can not afford an education, lack health insurance, it is a travesty that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> should now be seriously considering a huge tax cut for the very wealthy with no evidence that it will assist the economy,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said. Economists estimate that 80 percent of the benefit of a cut in taxes on capital gains _ profits from the sale of investments _ would go to people with incomes above $ 100,000 a year. Those with incomes above $ 200,000 would get tax cuts averaging $ 24,000. Republicans accused opponents of engaging in class-warfare rhetoric. `` This is a situation where everyone gains,'' said <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, contending a tax cut would benefit investors while producing increased revenue for the government to spend on social programs. `` You do n't get many deals better than that.'' The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, with backing of one of every four Democrats, approved a different capital gains cut in September. Present law fully taxes capital gains at the same rates that apply to wages and other income. The Packwood-Roth plan would mean lower taxes for capital gains; the longer an asset was held, the less of the profit from its sale would be taxed. Only 95 percent of the profit from the sale of an asset owned more than one year would be taxed. That percentage would increase by five points for each additional year up to seven; only 65 percent of the gain would be taxed when property owned more than seven years is sold. Investments in smaller companies would get an even better break; up to 50 percent could escape taxation. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> proposal, written by <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, R-Del., would combine a capital gains tax cut with expanded Individual Retirement Accounts Unlike existing IRAs, which permit some workers to avoid tax on contributions of up to $ 2,000 a year, the new version would simply exempt from tax any inerest earned on an IRA. In addition, a worker could make penalty-free withdrawals from the new IRAs for paying medical or education expenses.
