<HEAD>Slumping Regional Real Estate Market Leading to Rise In Foreclosures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An increasing number of residential properties are being sold on the auction block as the region's slumping real estate market prompts foreclosures on homes and developments that have trouble attracting buyers. `` We are seeing some foreclosures in our area. Where there used to be one or two, now there seems to be more,'' <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Sager </PERSON>, co-owner of Century 21 <ORGANIZATION> Sager </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Real </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estate </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lowell </LOCATION>, said Wednesday. The state <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> has seen a steep increase in foreclosures and auctions of all kinds across <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, although banking officials say owners of single-family homes have not been hit as hard as condominium developers. In 1987, 253 foreclosure filings culminated with an auction, meaning no one stepped in to pay off the mortgage. Last year the number rose to 546 and this year the total already has reached 1,100. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Trombly </PERSON>, recorder for the court, said the figures are not broken down into specific categories. `` It's everything,'' he said. `` It's condos. It's people who get laid off at <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> who get in over their heads.'' Banking officials blame much of the trouble on a real estate boom earlier this decade that led to an oversupply of building space, especially in condominiums. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenberg </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, which manages assets for banks, said some of the outlying areas from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> have been particularly troublesome for developers trying to sell condominiums. `` I think it's very clear in southern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> there was a bit more optimism exhibited than there should have been,'' <PERSON> Eisenberg </PERSON> said. `` Certainly there was not a lot of sober thought given to some of these projects.'' `` The foreclosures have accelerated at an accelerating pace,'' he said. `` Bankruptcy is a growth industry. And unfortunately, there is a lot of human suffering.'' Such an example came earlier this year, when <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Southborough </LOCATION>, the state's largest housing developer headquartered in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, filed for bankruptcy protection. <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> blamed the region's slow real estate market for his company's problems. Bankruptcy filings in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> are up about 50 percent from last year, and more than half are related to real estate projects, said <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Greiman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trustee whose office monitors bankruptcy cases for the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> region. <PERSON> Greiman </PERSON> said many people file for bankruptcy protection from creditors to buy time in the foreclosure process. `` You have developers with all these condo projects and no one buying them, so they have no cash flow to meet their expenses,'' she said. While condominium developers have been hit hard, bank officials say owners of single-family homes have not had as much trouble. Foreclosures on houses correlate less directly to the real estate market and stem more from general economic conditions, such as unemployment, which result in people having trouble paying their bills. Despite a wave recent layoffs in the high tech industry, regional unemployment remains relatively low, so forecasts of a recession have not yet translated to a surge of foreclosures on houses, said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, vice president at <ORGANIZATION> BancBoston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said that about 1.6 percent of his bank's residential loans are delinquent, compared with about 1.5 percent at the same time last year. Firms that conduct auctions, nonetheless, report that some homeowners are losing their houses to foreclosure. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Enik </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hyannis </LOCATION>, said many of these people bought second homes, such as around <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cod </LOCATION>, and now are having trouble making payments. These people also have trouble selling the homes because they were bought when prices were peaking, and the houses end up being auctioned. `` They thought they can always sell the property in the worst case,'' <PERSON> Enik </PERSON> said. `` But a lot of them can not sell.''
