<HEAD>Sears Takes Tower Off Market, Borrows $850 Million Against It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> removed the `` for sale'' sign Wednesday from the world's tallest building, saying it had decided not to sell <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> but to use it as collateral for an $ 850 million loan. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> said it expected to sign by mid-summer a 15-year convertible mortgage agreement with <ORGANIZATION> AEW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>, a limited partnership formed by <PERSON> Aldrich </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Waltch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a pension fund real-estate investment manager based in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. The deal will provide <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> with $ 815 million after expenses and give <ORGANIZATION> AEW </ORGANIZATION> an option to buy the 110-story downtown <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> landmark at the end of the loan period, said <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Fairweather </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. If <ORGANIZATION> AEW </ORGANIZATION> chooses to take possession of the 1,707-foot building rather than accept repayment of the loan, <PERSON> Fairweather </PERSON> said, the partnership would be required to pay <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> the balance of the tower's full 1989 value as well as a portion of its appreciated value. Chicago-based <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest retailer and a financial-services leader, announced just over a year ago that it would sell its 15-year-old headquarters building as part of a corporate restructuring designed to halt a slide in its profits. But after a prospective sale of the tower to Canadian developer <ORGANIZATION> Olympia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Developments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> fell through in September, <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> decided to take advantage of a drop in interest rates and refinance the tower, which it owns free and clear. When <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> announced plans on Oct. 31, 1988, to sell the building, `` we said that what we wanted to do was take out the appreciated value of this asset to invest in our core businesses and repurchase 10 percent of our shares,'' <PERSON> Fairweather </PERSON> said. `` While a sale seemed to be a better way to achieve our objectives when we made this announcement, by the time we did this deal, financing the building was a better alternative,'' he said. Interest rates on long-term loans for prime real estate such as <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> have fallen by as much as a full percentage point, to about 9 percent, in the past year, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Oharenko </PERSON>, managing partner in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> office of <ORGANIZATION> Cushman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Wakefield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a commercial real-estate firm. Commercial real-estate loans typically reflect up to 80 percent of a property's fair market value, he said. <PERSON> Fairweather </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> will use proceeds from the tower deal to pay down debt incurred through its repurchase over the past year of about 40 million shares of its stock at about $ 40 a share, and to invest in its core businesses, which include the <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> retailing division, <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> brokerage services, <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> insurance and Coldwell Banker real estate. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' restructuring also includes a plan to move its retailing headquarters from <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> to a yet-to-be built office complex in suburban <ORGANIZATION> Hoffman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estates </ORGANIZATION> by the end of 1992. Some of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s commercial real estate experts have said the 2 million square feet of office space to be vacated by the retailing division is badly in need of remodeling, both to modernize the facilities and to subdivide it into smaller areas. <PERSON> Fairweather </PERSON> indicated that <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> would be doing some remodeling in the tower. `` Even though it's a world-class building, we're aware of the fact there are opportunities to enhance its value and we'll be doing that,'' he said.
