<HEAD>Silver Soars, Gold and Platinum Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Silver futures prices soared to six-month highs Wednesday while gold and platinum, the recent leaders of the surging precious metals group, fell back. On other commodity markets, pork futures prices rose sharply amid talk of further food aid to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, grains and soybeans were mostly higher and energy futures were mixed. Silver futures settled 13 cents to 15.1 cents higher on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange with the contract for delivery in December at $ 5.538 a troy ounce, the highest price for a near-month silver contract since May 12. Gold finished $ 1.90 to $ 2.10 lower on the <ORGANIZATION> Comex </ORGANIZATION> with December at $ 392.80 a troy ounce; platinum settled $ 5.20 to $ 5.30 lower on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> with January at $ 520.40 a troy ounce. Precious metals prices have risen broadly since Oct. 13, when a 190-point plunge in the Dow Jones industrials average triggered a rush of investment dollars to the perceived safety of the metals. But the silver market has lagged behind gold and platinum, possibly because silver is in greater supply. From Oct. 13 through Tuesday, gold prices had risen by 7.5 percent, platinum by 6.9 percent and silver by just 4.9 percent. Silver played catch-up on Wednesday, pushing its gains since Friday the 13th to 7.8 percent. `` I view it as the rubber-band effect,'' said <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Savaiko </PERSON>, senior metals analyst with <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Platinum and gold had already had good moves and investors veiwed silver as too cheap relative to gold.'' Some traders express the silver-gold price relationship in terms of the number of ounces of silver it would take to equal the value of one ounce of gold. A ratio in excess of 70-to-1 is often interpreted by professional traders as a signal to buy silver and sell gold, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Steel </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. At the close of trading Tuesday, the silver-gold ratio was about 73-to-1, and it approached 74-to-1 early in Wednesday's session At that point, <PERSON> Steel </PERSON> said, `` the logical thing was to switch into the silver market.'' Pork futures prices skyrocketed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> after <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> probably would send more food aid to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. The government already has committed to send 10,000 metric tons of pork bellies to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> as part of a food-aid package. Firm cash markets also supported the pork and cattle markets. Live cattle settled .23 cent to .55 cent higher with December at 74.97 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .45 cent higher with November at 83.30 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent to 1.37 cents higher with December at 49.27 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .72 cent to 1.38 cents higher with February at 63.87 cents a pound. Grain and soybean futures finished mostly higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, paced by strength in the wheat market linked to dryness in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> winter wheat growing areas. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s confirmation of new sales of wheat to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> _ 50,000 metric tons apiece _ also helped the wheat market, as did a report of frost damage to wheat in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. Wheat settled 2 \ cents to 4 -RCB- cents higher with December at $ 4.05 a bushel; corn was \ cent lower to 2 cents higher with December at $ 2.39 -RCB- a bushel; oats were -RCB- cent to 1 -LCB- cents higher with December at $ 1.45 -RCB- a bushel; soybeans were -RCB- cent lower to 4 -RCB- cents higher with November at $ 5.79 -LCB- a bushel Wholesale home heating oil prices fell on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, weighed down by sluggish demand due to unusually warm weather on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. Crude oil and gasoline futures were mixed. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled .08 cent lower to .17 cent higher with December at $ 19.67 a barrel; heating oil was .05 cent to .61 cent lower with December at 57.13 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .20 cent lower to .30 cent higher with December at 50.61 cents a gallon.
