<HEAD>United: Pilots Must Continue to Fly Planes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> says its pilots union is bound by federal law to fly two new jumbo jets, but the pilots say that unless they have a new contract by a Nov. 22 deadline, those planes will be grounded. Lawyers for the company have told the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> that its members at <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> must continue to fly two new <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747-400s, <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Kathie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hardin </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s parent <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, declined comment on the issue. The planes, purchased last summer, fly from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to the Australian cities of <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Melbourne </LOCATION>. Within the next few months, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> plans to acquire a third 747-400 for its <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco-Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> route. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> pilots originally refused to fly the planes in a dispute over the size of cockpit crews. They later reversed their position as part of concessions granted during negotiations for a pilot-management buyout of <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>, and also agreed to fly four extra hours a month without pay. But after the pilot-management group failed to get financing for its $ 6.75 billion buyout proposal on Oct. 13, the pilots threatened to ground the planes on Nov. 22 unless there is sufficient progress toward a revised employee-led buyout, or toward a contract settlement. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> pilots have been working without a contract since April 1988. <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION>'s executive board is scheduled to discuss <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION>'s position on the new jetliners Thursday and Friday, as well as a contract proposal submitted by the company on Monday, Ms. <PERSON> Hardin </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> rejected as `` a piece of trash'' a <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> proposal offered last week _ the first since the buyout effort collapsed. Grounding one of those new planes for a year could reduce <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s revenue by about $ 50 million, industry experts say. <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> contends that <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION>, which represents the 7,000 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> pilots, would violate the federal Railway Labor Act by refusing to fly the planes, Ms. <PERSON> Hardin </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>'s taking the position that although it chose not to argue the point last summer, our not flying the 747-400s is illegal,'' she said. `` We say that there's no language in our existing contract for 747-400 flying.'' Ms. <PERSON> Hardin </PERSON> said she did not know what provision in the federal law would be applicable to the pilots union. An official at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mediation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said the law _ used in negotiating airline industry contracts _ generally requires pilots to abide by terms of their contracts, which commonly specify the types of planes they will fly. <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> might argue that the 747-400 is a derivative of an existing plane that is covered in the pilots' contract, said the official, who asked that he not be identified by name. But he said the airline would have to go to court to determine whether the law's provisions apply to the new planes. Such an action would be sure to damage the improved relationship between <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> management and pilots that resulted from participation in the failed buyout bid.
